R1:	5/35/18 update Don’t waste your money. These products are NOT made to last. The Robovac 11c replacement (3rd replacement) quit working properly. The vacuum now gives a false error as if there is something stuck. I spent $200 on a vacuum that lasted a year! We had a great initial experience with this product, but it was short lived. Unfortunately the warranty from the original purchase expired 60 days ago. I am now stuck with another Eufy Robovac that does not work, and all I get from customer support is 15% discount for another product that will not last. DON’T BUY IT!!!!! Update… Eufy customer support contacted me after my last review where I commented on the issues I was having after 3 months of continuous use. Once again, I have nothing but praises about their support. They offered another replacement, except this time with an 11c model. So far it works great, as did the first two. I hope this model lasts longer. I purchased this in march and was very pleased with it. The robovac does an excellent job navigating through our lower floor while we are asleep. It works quietly and we woke up to a clean floor. I am now on my second RoboVac thanks to Eufy's excellent customer service and running into the same problems I had with my original purchase. The vacuum does an excellent job avoiding walls and large objects, not so much when it comes to chair legs. After 3 months of ocasional bumping into chairs, the lens that covers the sensor gets scratched and becomes cloudy. Now I wake up to the sound of the robovac ramming into walls instead of avoiding them, just like my original did as well. I've tried cleaning the plastic lens but only works momentarily. Now it's also starting to have problems docking into the charging station, which I presume is due to the cloudy lens cover. It's sad that such a good product fails because o a small lens cover. Some small tweaks in design should fix this problem and allow the vacuum to work properly for longer than 3 months. Hey Eufy! How about placing a better rubber on the bumper to protect the lens cover, or changing the material ? If not for that this vac would have had a 5 star

R2:	UPDATE 1 on 07/31/17 Added a picture of my low-to-medium carpet. Also, the 4/3 beep has not come back yet. ORIGINAL REVIEW: I have been using iRobot for many years. Bought this Eufy Robovac 11 when it was on sale and initially like it very much since it is quieter and clean well for my living room with hardwood floor. I have the robot programmed for every day sessions. The Eufy does not work well for other rooms with carpet, though. The biggest problem was with the 4-beep fatal syndrome: Just after 5 weeks, suddenly the robot stopped working with 4-beep and 3-beep. I did all steps as detailed in the manual to no avail. Since Amazon only allows returning for 4 weeks, I decided to investigate a bit further. It turns out that both the main brush and a side brush got stuck even after I cleared all obstacles. So, I took the stuck brushes out, spray some WD-40 lithium grease into the wells. Put the brushes back and rocked the brushes back and forth to pass the sticking point. The robot is working again and continue to work after more than a week ( will see how long will it work). In conclusion, the problems come from the gearbox of the brush - when it got stuck, it cannot reset itself. Even though I decided to keep this Eufy robot, I bought the iRobot 650 - a time proven machine that will work for all rooms (my current iRobot 5XX has been working for >5 years but I need a programmable one).

R3:	Very displeased. It bounces around the room as if it is completely lost, using 90 degree angles whenever it hits a wall. It gets stuck under everything, our couch, inside the maze our dining room chairs make, under the couch again, on carpet runners, bath mats, cords... you name it. I found that we had to "eufy"-proof our house as if we were introducing a new child to a home. Couch pillows scattered around the couch so that it won't try to get underneath, pick up any USB cords, put down a 2x4 bumper wall around our dining room set, prop open the door to our laundry room that it always manages to close itself into, etc. The list goes on and on. Maybe this is par for the course with all robotic vacuums, and if that's the case, I say save yourself the trouble. EDIT: I must thoroughly applaud Eufy/Anker Customer Service. They discovered this review and despite my purchasing this product months ago went far above and beyond. They quickly worked to thoroughly understand the problems I had with my Eufy, going so far as to ask for a video of the problems and engaging a product engineer. Sadly nothing could be done about my specific problems, but Eufy surprised me again by offering a full refund, including providing me with a free item of my choosing for the trouble. I have no hesitation in buying another Eufy/Anker product because of their exceptional Customer Service, despite the issues I had with this one particular product.

R4:	I purchased this having read reviews stating the RoboVac 11 gets stuck and rarely makes it back to its dock. In my old apartment, I had little problems and absolutely loved this unit. No, it didn't make it back to its dock every day, but 9/10 it would run for its 2-2.5 hour long battery life and did a great job with the pet hair. RoboVac 11 does not do air vents. AT ALL. Or the ledge to a step. RoboVac 11 rarely runs for longer than 10 minutes now, before getting stuck on a air vent.

R5:	UPDATE AGAIN: I loved my Eufy the fist 3 months. Had an issue with something and Eufy replaced the vacuum. Six months later I started having error codes, but was preparing to deploy so waited till I returned. Upon my return, my 12 month warranty ran out by 10 days. They sent me a new charging station, but that did not help. Now 1 month after that, the battery is apparently dead. No replacement. No help from Eufy. I also bought a EUFY for my brother, who after 9 months had similar issues and just threw it away. Great vacuum for a year, but not after that. I also own a RUMBA. It is way louder, but even after spending an unfortunate night outside in the rain, it continues to clean every day! I have had it 5 years! NO issues, except the couple of days after it's escape from the house. Spend the money on the Ruma. UPDATE: It has been a year and my brother and I have had issues. There is a 12 month warranty on these units. My first issue was resolved with customer support replacing my Eufy. Recently my Eufy has been beeping 4 times while charging. This happens at random times, usually around 2 am when I am trying to sleep. Apparently my brother had the same issue and he just stopped using his all together. I have changed the filter, roller, and brushes. I have let the battery die then charged it fully. Nothing helped. After doing all I know to do I contacted Eufy one week after my 12 month warranty was up. Guess what....yep....no help. Other than the annoying random beeping at odd hours, the vacuum is still working fine. I guess since both of our vacuums started having random error codes within 8 months of purchase, that must mean there is an issue with most of them. Or we are the most unlucky people ever. I purchased two of these. One as a gift and one for myself. I am a huge Rumba fan, but this had so many reviews about how quiet it was so I decided to try it. Plus you couldn't beat the price! My brother has a 2 year old, and is a super technology freak. He was skeptical at first, but after a week, he loves it. He was impressed by how much this little guy picked up. It is quiet enough to run when the baby is sleeping. My brother runs his daily and has carpet and a dog. Finally a gift for my super picky brother that he loves. The one I purchased for myself if SUPER quiet as well. It fits under my furniture better than the Rumba. I run mine daily and have a cat and a dog. After about 20 days I started getting an error. The nice thing is this unit tells you what the problem is, however, it doesn't shut up after beeping, it just keeps beeping. After extensive cleaning and brush removal, and trying to fix it, I was unable to clear the error. I notified Eufy. So far the customer service has been ok. I am still waiting to exchange it for a new one. If it fails within 30 days they replace it. It does come with a 12 month warranty. While I am having an issue with the Eufy, I highly recommend it. It is a true vacuum, unlike Rumba which is more like a broom. It is quieter, smarter, and has a few more options. Hopefully Eufy customer service gets on the ball or else I will change my review about them.

R6:	After 5 months of use I have become less enthusiastic about this vaccum. It's still a decent value, but there are quite a few cons about it. First the pros: I really sucks stuff up. Works especially well on hard wood floors. It's quiet. It's easy to maintain. Everything comes apart easily and intuitively. And you WILL need to maintain it to keep it functioning well. There's no point in having a programmable vacuum because all of the brushes and filters need to be completely cleaned out before or after every use. Now the cons: The big one and the reason for this review is the battery life seems to be significantly degrading. I have owned the vacuum for 5 months and run it every day on average. This morning the battery lasted about 1 hour. That is not long enough to do a very good job when the vacuum is as dumb as this one. And the brings me to the next con. There seems to be very little intelligence to the vacuum's programming. It will cover a small area over and over and over, until finally I notice and move it to another part of the house that needs vacuuming. It will get "lost" for long periods of time under furniture or tables, unable to find its way out. And the final con: the vacuum gets stuck. A lot. Depending on the obstacles in your house, you may have to rescue this vacuum a dozen times during 1 cleaning session. It gets stuck on things like: the underside of furniture and cabinets, floor vents, cords, etc. And sometimes it is stuck on nothing. You just have to press the button and it starts up again. But it's annoying that I can't turn it on and forget it. I have to keep checking to make sure it doesn't need to be rescued for one reason or another. Bottom line: It's a decent value and $200 for a robovac, but I'm very concerned about the degrading battery life. I will update the review to let you know how much worse it gets. EDIT: 11/20/17 The Eufy has become worthless. It stops every couple minutes and needs to be restarted manually. And this is on a light color clean hardwood floor. Time to contact customer service :( EDIT 2: 11/23/17 Eufy is working again after I found an object lodged in it. I have to say customer service is great. I think there is very little risk to trying this vacuum. As far as the battery life goes, customer service wanted me to test the battery life when manually plugged in, charged for at least 6 hours, and run on ONLY hard floors. Doing this the vacuum ran for about 2 hours. Which is fine, but unfortunately most of my house is covered in carpeting. When the vacuum runs on carpeting it only runs for slightly over an hour. Reading between the lines, this vacuum is really designed for hard floors and a few area rugs.

R7:	My wife and I work from home and live in a 3 dog household. We purchased this to save time, as without it, you would need to sweep 2-3 hours per day just to keep up with the fur and debris the dogs bring in from outside. The Eufy was great for the first few months, but then the problems started. I changed the filters regularly, and even bought a new rolling brush when the first one started falling apart after a few months. When I received the new roller it worked fine for a few weeks, now it continuously beeps 4 times with a solid red light *indicating rolling brush is stuck*...this is a new rolling brush, but hell I took it out cleaned it out, changed the filter and went about my day...the error continued to happen no matter how clean the brush was, and the robovac became unusable. I purchased this in May of last year, it made it to February, Eufy wants a video of the issue to be emailed to them to verify issue, then I ship it to them, then they ship me one back...all in all, you are talking weeks without the RoboVac I purchased to save us time, instead of going through this hassle (is the video really necessary being that I will be shipping you the defective item anyway and you could verify then??) I purchased a cheaper model by a different manufacturer, designed for pet households. My warning to pet owners is, if you are using this to get rid of large amounts of dog hair, the shelf life of this model is not worth the price. Very disappointed, and will not purchase Eufy again.

R8:	I was a big fan of this product--until it stopped working a few months ago. (It lasted all of 15 months.) I was getting the same 4 beep error, which indicates a stuck rolling brush. I diligently cleaned the robovac thoroughly, and watched numerous YouTube videos on how to clean and troubleshoot it. I even bought replacement parts to see if a new rolling brush would fix the problem. It did not. I recently contacted the manufacturer, and they were of no help. Because it stopped working after 1 year, it was not covered by warranty any longer. The company offered me a $30 credit to BUY A NEW ROBOVAC. And I guess just throw this one away..? You're welcome, environment! I searched for a local repair shop that might be willing to repair my robovac and I couldn't find a single one. I regret ever recommending this unit to my parents, who bought one, and my next door neighbor, who also bought one, because I know when those units fail (and I'm sure they will) they will wind up in landfill along with this one and many, many others.

R9:	The vacuum worked great until it started spinning in a circle after about 18 months. Then I found out that if something is wrong with this product after the 12 month warranty expires, the company won't fix or replace it, nor do they have any replacement parts. I took it apart myself and figured out that one of the plastic gears in the wheel wore down and needed to be replaced. This part probably would cost about 5 cents if they had spares for sale. The only help they offered was a discount on a new vacuum (I think 10%). I ended up buy a spare wheel from another brand via eBay, hoping they had a similar gear. That cost $21, and I had to take one of the gears from that wheel and cut it down with a hacksaw. It was similar enough to work. So my vacuum is working again, but it cost me quite a bit of time for a minor issue. Beware before you buy from this company that after one year your product is trash if it has an even minor problem, assuming that you don't want to go through a similar hassle.

R10:	UPDATE: They Eufy no longer works! After a year it started spinning in circles and just continuesly beeps. It will run for 5 mins and then beep again in circles. I will try a different brand next time. This is my first RoboVac and it has far passed my expectations!! The cleaning capability of this thing is insane! I have 3 cats and 3 dogs with Hard Wood Floors and Tile through out the Down Stairs. I hit the Auto mode every morning before work and it runs for 1:20 mins. When I come home from work the Tile and Hardwood floors are spotless. With so many animals I was always sweeping and vacuuming before and now I don't need to. The Robot gets all corners and crevasses along with the middle and sides of the floors. Last night for fun I tested it upstairs on the carpet. I baby gated the stairs off and let it do its thing. Again, ran perfect and cleaned 100x better than my upright Vac. The one thing I will say is that when running on Carpet I dumped the tray a couple of times along with picking out my wife's and daughters hairs from the rollers. I don't see any way this could have been avoided as I used to do that also with my upright! I have run in both regular and Max mode and they both work great. Max mode has more suction so I tend to always run in that. The sound of this Vac is very quiet, you can deff run it while a baby is sleeping with out issues. So far I have had this Vac and week and don't know how I have ever lived without it. Thanks you Eufy RoboVac 11, you made my life so much easier. Don't hesitate to make this purchase!

Customer service asked me to send them videos and pictures of the vacuum so I did. They asked me to try a few at home tests to make sure the sensor was clear which it was (it was brand new) They then offered to send me an upgraded vacuum when the upgrade was done (mid December). I have been trying that new vacuum out, and have to say, it is more of a headache than anything. It gets caught under our couch, bed, side tables, and even our fridge. If the room is the slight bit dark the vacuum will run into everything! It is easier for me to just back to sweeping myself. Customer service is AMAZING!!! I wanted to love this vacuum but I don't :( I have had this for a month now. It has yet to go through a whole cycle without stopping, I make sure nothing is stuck, start it back up and 10 minutes later it is beeping at me. I have found it going in circles over and over again.

R13:	The Eufy RoboVac 11 does perform the basic function of sucking without manual intervention for brief interludes. However it seems incapable of navigating the most basic geographic features of a relatively typical single-floor apartment with hardwood floors and a couple of low-tuft area rugs. It gets stuck on the edge of rugs, under chairs, in corners, in wide open spaces, and, oddly, near shoes. The vacuum seems to follow a complex pattern in its cleaning process which leaves large swathes of the apartment untouched while smaller sections have started to develop tracks. The “return to base” feature has never worked, with the robovac beeping out its deep angst about its desire to tunnel through walls and furniture to return to its charging station while possessing none of the boring or ballistic capabilities that would be required to fulfill its mission. My 3 year old has named the device “Fred” and walks around complaining to anyone who will listen that “Fred is sooooo annoying”. I admit at times my wife and I will vent in obscenity laden tirades at the incessant error noises Fred emits and though I have noticed no discernible change in the machine’s performance following such outbursts, I sometimes detect a hint of moral superiority in its beeping. In short, if you are seeking an insecure, underperforming robot vacuum requiring near-constant supervision I highly recommend the Eufy RoboVac 11.

R14:	We loved our Eufy (affectionately named "Ollie" for some un-rememberable reason...) for a year and some change. He was our little workhorse; the dog furminator; the sucker of dust; and the occasional iPhone charging cord eater. But, about a month or so after the warranty ran out, our beloved Ollie started glitching out every time we used him. 4 beeps on a solid red light (rolling brush stuck indicator warning) both during operation and while sitting on the charging port. I cleaned that sucker out; replaced the spinners; lubed up his innards; tried everything to no avail. Finally, I contacted customer support. To their credit, they are polite and responsive, but they won't offer anything but 15% off a replacement unit or a replacement rolling brush, which they tell me won't fix the problem. This leads me to believe (and reading other reviews) that this is a recurring and well-known problem at the company. I hope that the company will do the right thing and replace the unit altogether, or offer a more substantial discount off a higher quality unit. I'd be happy to update the review to a higher level, because, when it works, this is a fantastic piece of gear. But, given the suspiciously inconvenient timing of its premature demise, I can't give anything but a 1-star until it's made right.

R15:	My wife thought I had lost my mind when I purchased this now she loves it. We have 2 greyhounds and it is nice to have the floors vacuumed each night as it keeps the hair, sand and dust cleaned up. We have dark vinyl plank flooring that shows dirt so this is nice. This is our first robot vacuum and it has been a pretty good experience so far. As one reviewer opined that it acts like a "drunken frisbee" for the first while then seems to get more efficient. I still think it tends to wander a lot and after 3 months of almost daily use it seems to be running into walls more. I carefully cleaned the front lens and it seemed to help some but for a while the vacuum sounded like it was trying to break into our bedroom at night. Visions of a robot apocalypse come to mind... My review is a 3 not 5 because I am concerned about the longevity of the unit if it keeps loosing it's way and it bashing into walls every time it runs. At some point that is likely to cause some failures. Time will tell. Update July 19, 2018 We are up to just over 13 months with this vacuum. We use it almost every night and only when we are away it doesn't run. That means that it has cleaned our floors well over 300 times since we received it. That's at least 5 times a week and we haven't had any other problems other than what is noted above. It still runs into everything but keeps on working. Many reviewers have seen a failure after 12 months or so with only weekly or slightly more frequent cleaning so I am not sure why ours is still going. I would like to get at least a couple years out of this...hopefully.

R17:	UPDATE: Dont waste your money on this one unless you have a small, empty room that needs vacuuming. It doesn't do a complete job and the unit is constantly getting stuck somewhere. You're better off paying a cleaning service or put the money towards a Neato or Roomba. PROS. Does a good job picking up dog hair. My husband has serious allergies and we have a Lab that is in the process of shedding. It's as though she's on a payroll somewhere and is paid per eah time i have to sweep up fur which i did several times a day! When I set the vacuum to start running my husband was constantly clearing his thrpat and coughing. The longer the vacuum ran that less he coughed until he stopped completely. It senses things in its way and avoid it. Our old Neato was on a seek and destroy mission. It would roll over any and everything. This also doesnt fall down the stairs. CONS: I had to get up and rescue it from places where it got stuck. By that I mean it went underneath a rocking chair and kept going back and forth between the two rocker thingies instead of getting out. It wanted to go that way ---> and was going to continue trying until it gave up. It stopped and started beeping which is how i knew it had an issue. I know it has sensors because it would approach things and then back away except there. Another thing is that it continued to vacuum the same areas over and over. The Neato we had used its laser to pick up haair and dust. When Neato couldnt detect anything else (i would see it turning to try to sense things) it would return to based. I couldnt figure out the rhyme or reason behind the Eufy's cleaning method. it wanted to clean our foyer over and over until i guess the battery went dead.I BOTTOM LINE: i cant see setting the timer and leaving it to work unsupervised. Ideally I would set it to start running prior to us getting home from work. I can see now that I would be pissed because the thing got itself penned in somewhere and didnt do anything all day. I have to rescue it several tiimes each time it runs but I'm pleased with its performance other than that. I would buy this again. it does a very good job removing the dog hair and it's so quiet that it can run without drowning out the tv.

R18:	so far so good, but because it is so good at avoiding things and not ramming things, I can't get it to go through my dining table chair legs to clean under the table. Roomba is very loud and hit things, but it cleaned under my table well. Eufy is very quiet compared to Roomba. I'd probably get a Roomba again versus Eufy if I were to do it all over, but this is ok for the price so I'll just stick with it. Update: after getting a replacement, the new one still won't go under stuff that has lots of overhead clearance. Short of using the remote to make it go where it needs to, which defeats the whole purpose, I won't get a complete cleaning. Wanted to like it soooo bad because it's so quiet, and lots of great reviews, but I'm going to have to return it and get another loud roomba. Update: increased to 3 stars due to AMAZING customer support.

R19:	I recently purchased the Eufy Robovac 11 on Amazon during Prime day. It was a great price, especially compared to the competitors, and I was really looking forward to using it. I bought a Roomba 650 about two months prior, and after reading reviews on the Eufy Robovac 11, I decided I would give the Roomba to my best friend who just bought her first home, since the Eufy seemed to have better suction and was overall a better vacuum. I had to withdraw my offer to my friend, since I ended up keeping my Roomba 650. Some of the major areas where I think the Eufy fell short, compared to my Roomba 650: - Eufy does not get to all corners of the room (hardwood floors). Instead, it stops about 6-8 inches away and turns. My floors are darker brown, but I read reviews where people say they had dark or black floors and it worked without any issue. - Eufy does not have as good of suction as the Roomba 650. There were many times where the dust bin was completely clean and it would roll over lint or dust, and would not pick it up. I tried troubleshooting the device, and was not able to figure out anything that would successfully make it pick up all dust in it's path, during one pass (and I am talking about a FEW dog hairs, and maybe some lint from my wool rug that have migrated over to the hardwoods). - The patterns in which it travels across my floor is not smart. I don't expect it to be actually "smart" because I know it's not a smart vac, but it would often keep going in circles after bumping into something, and would take a few laps to get out of that cycle. It just wasn't very efficient. - Half of the time, it would very gently bump something. The other half of the time, it would slam into railings, furniture, etc. - It really struggles on carpet. It is much slower, and it has become stuck on my rug as well. - It does not make it back to the charger all of the time. - The brushes and/or fan on the vac seemed to fling dust the opposite way sometimes - Brushes could be more heavy duty. My Roomba (bought used!) brushes are stronger and don't look like they have had near as much wear in two months of regular use, compared to the Eufy, which was tested about two or three times at most. The benefits of Eufy Robovac 11, compared to the used Roomba 650 that I previously bought two months ago: - The Eufy is SO QUIET! My roomba is incredibly loud, and I LOVE HOW QUIET THE EUFY IS! - It is seriously so quiet, that I am so amazed that it's possible to be a robot vacuum. I just wish it had more power and suction. - it is QUIET - MAN IS IT QUIET! - Battery life is great - Design is beautiful and clean - I did not use the remote, but I like that it came with one. Again, I really, REALLY wanted to love the Eufy, and hope they make a better robot vacuum in the future. :) Each time that I have run the Eufy, I have had to turn the Roomba on after the Eufy finishes to pick up everything the Eufy left behind. This resulted in me only using the Roomba. In summary, if suction worked better, and if it sucked up a little bit of dog hair/lint in one pass, I would have kept it. MAYBE mine is defective... no clue. I really wish this would have worked out!!!

R20:	Works well, but I would not recommend letting it run when there is no one around to check on it. It has a habit of getting stuck under the bed or running over the leaves of plants and then beeping for assistance. That said, I'll get up on Saturdays, turn it on, and let it run loose while I'm doing chores around the house. I maintain it doesn't like to be alone, because it always seems to be whirring about in whichever room I happen to be working in (not a complaint, just an observation). We have not had any issues with how it cleans, only that it will occasionally get stuck under the bed (it's a low frame on the bed). UPDATE: In the middle of 2018, "Jeffrey" as my husband dubbed it, started to launch on his own. About 3:00 in the afternoon, he'd start out about the house. That was fine on the weekends, but during the week, he'd get stuck. So it became a game after work to come home and find Jeffrey. We had a few power failures and suddenly Jeffery was starting out about 2:00am. We'd be awakened either by his cries for help or his banging into the closet in our bedroom. I carefully went over the instructions and set him up to start at noon every day. He never automatically went out again. Worse, whenever I'd start him to go, he'd immediately return to the home base. I ordered new parts (filters, brushes, etc.), cleaned him well, reset him, and tried again. He was fine for a week and then got progressively worse. At times he'd spin for a bit in the same spot, move about three feet, and then head home. It was as if he had Alzheimer's. He couldn't remember what he was supposed to do, where he was supposed to go, and where he had just been. We had a simple ceremony at the garbage can on a cool winter Saturday. RIP Jeffrey.

R21:	He worked okay at the vacuum-ing part, but he gets stuck on EVERYTHING. The divider between hard wood and tile floors? Stuck. Kitchen mat? Stuck. Tile around the fireplace? Stuck. Kitchen cabinet overhang? Stuck. I "baby proofed" my house really well for him (no wires, curtains, etc) and he still got stuck within 20 minutes of beginning operations every time. I used him pretty sporadically when the dogs dragged a lot of stuff in from outside, grass debris etc, and he was okay at taking care of that. I never had him set on a schedule because he got stuck too much, so I used him maybe once a month or a little more. After 12.5 months (right after warranty expired) he died. He will make a beeping sound when I attempt to turn him on and then his light flashes like he needs to be charged I guess. I bought the SquareTrade warranty for him as well but they're feigning ignorance about my purchase (despite being shown the transaction) and won't do anything about it. So while I WOULD recommend the extended warranty, the extended warranty is also apparently a waste of money as well.

R24:	There were a lot of concerning aspects about this unit right out of the box but for the relatively low price I would say they were manageable. The next issue out of the box is that it has very poor coverage. The areas it does go over get cleaned well but it seems to go over and over the same areas while neglecting large swaths. The above issues put the unit in the 2-3 star range for me but now after 4 months the unit no longer works. I get solid red light 4 beeps error for a stuck rotating brush a minute into cleaning. This occurs even if the rotating brush is removed from the unit. I have now seen multiple people reporting the same issue and it is clear they don't have a solution. Customer service is making me jump through hoops to try and troubleshoot the problem but the issue is widespread enough now that it should either have a known resolution or not.

R31:	UPDATE-2: These are crap. The brushes tangle on short dog hair constantly, it will leave clumps of fur about even after emptying, and it gets stuck on EVERYTHING! UPDATE-1: Eufy has exchanged my unit and all is well again. No more squeaks! One thing I noticed after watching my Eufy Robovac clean, is that if you have a lot of sunlight on the floor from a sliding glass door, make sure you close the blinds. The IR from the sunlight overpowers the Eufy's drop/cliff sensors and it will avoid the area. Basically, it's scared of sunlight. After communicating this to support they said it will be reviewed for future product updates and that the current model wouldn't be resolved with a replacement so I'm keeping 1 star off. Otherwise, I'm happy with my purchase. I had a Roomba 600 series before this and it was twice the price. I am generally impressed with how well the Eufy unit cleans. Only issue after a few months of use would be it has started squeaking intermittently and we don't know where it is coming from. I cleaned the roller ball and the two rubbery wheels pretty good but squeaky squeak it goes around corners and such. Not a huge issue, we just set it to clean when nobody is home rather than overnight.

R33:	After going through 3 of these units, I gave up. After just a week or 2 of use, the first unit stopped vacuuming and sounded a 4 beep sequence for maintenance. I followed the instructions in the manual, but could not clear the error. So I called tech support for help and they also had me go through a few steps to clear the error to no avail. So, since I still had time left in my Amazon 30 day return window, I returned this unit for a 2nd unit. The second unit was lazy. After initiating the bot to clean, it would move away from the charging base 2 or 3 feet, do a circle and then go straight back home. I found that, it would go on and work if I would unplug the charging base so it could no longer find its way back home. But that took half the fun out of owning the robot since I had to manually return it home to charge after the battery went dead. Now that my 30 day window had expired on the original unit purchased from Amazon, I had to call Eufy customer service about the problem. Eufy's service was excellent! They were great about getting me a 3rd unit in a very timely fashion with a little headache as possible. But, the 3rd unit ended up having the same issue as the 2nd. Totally bummed out, I called Eufy customer service again. This time, they suggested I get a full refund and purchase their newer unit. I agreed. Then much to my dismay, I found the newer unit to be $80 more than what I paid. Naaaa.... why pay $299 when I can purchase an Ecovacs Deebot N79 for $199. I see it has great reviews too. I'm surprised the Eufy has great reviews with as much trouble as I've had.

R34:	This is a cute little robot that has a practical side. While it is still basically a fancy toy, it does pick up dust, hair, crumbs and like detritus from about 90 % of the floor. While nowhere near as thorough as a good vacuum cleaning, it will keep the dust down between vacuum sessions. It is fairly quiet and it goes underneath beds and cabinets (needs about 4" of clearance to easily get under there). However, it will get occasionally hung up on area rugs and does best on flat wood or tiled floors. It does not do a good job on corners, tight spaces or thick rugs. The dirt holding cup is small and needs to be emptied every time you run it, and sometimes it just dies when it runs out of charge, not making it back to its base. I thought it remembered the path it takes to not go over the same area repeatedly, but it just cuts a random path across the floor, over and over, until most of the easily accessible area has been covered. These are the first domestic robots and still need a lot of improvement to be effective. Don't expect it to eliminate the need for a real vacuum cleaner, or even to do light vacuuming flawlessly. However, if you have pet hair, or enjoy being on the cutting edge of domestic tech, then this little guy might be a worthwhile investment.

R35:	This vacuum is poorly designed from a functional perspective and is not worth any amount of money in my opinion. I bought this from seeing it advertised on CNET and thought it was a good deal considering the irobots can go as high as $1000 or more. It was a brand new unit and worked perfectly the first 3 times. The 4th time it began beeping error notifications. I didn't think much of it at the time and reset it and it functioned for a short while before beeping error notifications again. I had only owned it about a month at this point and just put it in the closet with the intent on investigating it further another time. Well some time had passed and before I knew it, it had just passed the warranty expiration date. I had decided to have it diagnosed and possibly replaced but was out of warranty. Waiting too long to make a warranty claim was my fault I admit, and though I tried to get a free replacement, I ultimately had to pay to get a replacement. I will say that the customer service representative I worked with "Sebrina" throughout the process was very helpful and understanding. She eventually offered me a refurbished model at about half what I paid for the new one and I did buy it. One day after initially charging it up and putting it to work, it began exhibiting the same issues as the new one. I contacted Sebrina and she arranged to send me a different one, this time a refurbished Robovac 11s and it worked for about 2 uses and failed as well. This is vacuum #3. I contacted her again and provided video to show the malfunctioning vacuums as I had done previously. She was quite perplexed and assured me she would do what she could to make it right. I ended up getting a new replacement at no cost about 2 months ago but have been reluctant to use it as I have not had a good experience with this product. My advice to those who buy this vacuum is to be aware of your remaining warranty period. They will not replace it if it is out of warranty. They do have some of the best customer service representatives I've ever had to deal with, so there is a bit of consolation there if you ever have to contact them.

R45:	I gave this vacuum 6 month of use before a review. Live in a home with open floor plan, all hard wood and tile flooring with one low pile rug. Frankly, this vacuum has been a major disappointment. Clean pattern is poor, missed lots of spots even when run for full battery life. Sensors are poor, stop randomly in mid room and changes direction like it senses something but other times will hit wall several times before changing direction. Battery life is ok but it takes 30-45 minutes at it slow seeking battery housing speed to find the charges, even when in the same room. I would say 1/2 the time I find it somewhere completely dead as it never made it back/found the charger. The brush gets even small fibers stuck in it very easily. Suction seems average at best and machine is pretty loud when running. Remote is easy to use and set-up. I have purchased another brand now about 1 month ago. Name brand and its WAY better across the board. Recommend you pass on this vacuum.

R46:	This is our first robot vacuum and we've had mixed results. While the vacuum does a decent job of making the vacuuming the home easier, more often than not, it gets stuck or need intervention. Perhaps, the newer model has addressed the shortcomings of the model I purchased, but here are some limitations with the model we've used for several months. -Difficulty going over raised mats. In our kitchen, we have foam mats on the floor and this vacuum has trouble going over it, often getting stuck and letting out beeps to let me know that it's stuck. Sometimes, it doesn't get stuck, so it's hard to know when it'll and when it won't. -Difficulty clearing under some furniture. Sometimes, the vacuum will get stuck underneath a dresser while other times, it'll go under just fine. When it does get stuck, it's at an angle that suggests some part of the vacuum is raised that causes it to get stuck. -Not being able to find its way home. The area around the charger has to be very clear or the vacuum often takes a detour and gets to the charger in a longer path or doesn't find its way to the charger at all. -Bumping into chair legs. Large objects are easier for this vacuum to avoid contact, but for chair legs, it'll often run into it and then change course. The bumper thankfully has a damper so that the impact doesn't impart too much force, but I don't recommend using this around expensive furniture where scuffs and scratches are undesirable. -Can't purchase another charging base. Amazon doesn't seem to sell the charging base by itself to help with using this on multiple locations. All in all, a good first effort by Eufy. I'm guessing the second gen and after has addressed some of these shortfalls?
	S1:	This is our first robot vacuum and we've had mixed results.
	PosTag:	[DT, VBZ, PRP$, JJ, NN, NN, CC, PRP, VBP, VBN, VBN, NNS, .]
	NerTag:	[O, O, O, ORDINAL, O, O, O, O, O, O, O, O, O]

R47:	ORIGINAL REVIEW: I love this vacuum it does a great job of cleaning, however, it is constantly getting stuck and it will go in the same spot over and over and neglect other parts of the room. If you have a large open space that doesn't have a lot of things like chairs in it (it gets stuck under our couch and entertainment center every single day) then this is a great budget vacuum robot for you. We have even tried to block the sections of our living room where it gets stuck but it knocks those things down by bumping into it and then gets stuck anyways. It would be best to run it when someone is home to make sure that it doesn't get stuck. UPDATE: BEWARE, within less than a year the battery died and vacuum broke down -- customer service sent me a replacement of the same model and it too broke down within the same time frame as the first vacuum. Customer service told me that the warranty only covered the original purchased vacuum and not the replacement so I spent way too much money on two vacuums that have a shorter lifespan than the $80 vacuum I bought at Walmart. I loved having this machine running while I am away for those "in between" sweeps but they died out on me so quickly that it is not worth the price. Plus, it is only adults in my house and we treated this machine well, kept up on maintenance, and made sure it didn't get stuck for it to still die out in less than a year. Save your money and spend a little more for a brand model and it will probably last you a lot longer than this one will and it will be less of a pain constantly checking on it.

R49:	Update July 2019: Bumper sensor failed again in the either repaired or refurbished replacement. Will be sending a strongly worded note to the company after I post this update. My parents Roomba 690 has held up much better and they're currently on sale for prime day. Spend the extra $ and get something that won't breakdown within a year. Update Jan 2019: sent it in. Not sure if they fixed mine or just sent me a refurbished replacement. We'll see how long this one lasts. Still mad that I had to spend money to fix it after only having it for a little over a year, but I'm happy to have it working again. When it does work, it vacuums nicely. If you own one and notice it gets stuck more often or is running into things, I would send it in. Looking back, I realize those two issues were a symptom of the bumper sensors starting to fail. They completely failed about 4 months after the first sign of a problem. Aside from the bumper sensor issue, I do really like the vacuum. We run it everyday, moving it from room to room because it gets stuck on door jams where our floors change from wood to tile. We empty it after every run because we have a very furry household. I take it apart regularly to clean the brushes and give it a wipedown. Comparing Roomba 690 and Eufy RoboVac 11: We bought our parents a roomba 690 for xmas 2017. They use it at our family's cabin to cut down on dust and the dreaded black fly massacre that happens every week (they love the warm metal building and die by the hundreds). They like it because they can turn it on via their phones on Friday mornings before they head up there for the weekend, which can't be done with the Eufy model. It is taller than the Eufy so it doesn't fit under some pieces of furniture. The cabin floor is concrete and the Roomba has no problem picking up the hummingbird sized flies. We've also put the Roomba up in the loft, which has builder's grade carpet, and it does a great job. I would say that both vacuums clean equally well, although, I haven't compared them side to side. Dec 2018: I took the thing apart and it still stops every few minutes. I'm on the hook for a $200 vacuum that doesn't work unless I want to spend another $80 (not including shipping) in order to fix it. It's not a product made to last. Will save up and purchase a vacuum with a longer warranty with a company that stands behind its products.

R56:	For the most part, I've enjoyed this RoboVac. It does a wonderful job cleaning - but my 3 star review comes from it getting stuck on quite a multitude of things. It would be much nicer if it was a little more agile in getting itself out of situations. Some examples include: Basically every register on the carpet. To be fair, this vacuum is meant more specifically for hard surfaces than carpet - but it gets stuck on every single register we have on the carpet. I've resorted to sitting them all sideways in the floor so that it bumps into it instead of running it over. The feet of my Lazyboy chair. It jumps up on them and gets itself stuck. The flashing between the hardwood and the carpet. There's about a 3/8 inch jump up, and while it's trying to round the corner of the doorjamb and go up it at the same time it gets stuck. Behind all of the plants. We've got potted plants in the house near windows, and the vac will get stuck trying to turn the corner between the pot and the wall. We've tried moving the plants slightly closer or further away, but no luck. Between the feet of the bed and the wall. Same story as the flowerpots. It does do a good job of sensing steps or drop-offs and stopping, but that's all it does. It runs next to it and stops and starts beeping at you. I suppose this is nice, but it's not quite what I had expected. I was thinking it would back away and continue in the opposite direction. Instead it just stops dangerously close to the edge. (Be warned if you're a pet owner and your pet loves to follow the vac around. Our pup almost knocked it over the edge!) Sorry for the novel review - but I wanted to share my full experience. Hope this helps your shopping! Best, Cody Ritter

But almost 2 years to the month it began with a red flashing indicator and 4 beeps. The label on the bottom of the device indicates "RoboVac's power level is too low." How this has happened with it always on it's charging base I'd love to know. That "long-lasting" 14.8v lithium-ion battery they tout, 5.82v is where it sits even after charging it directly plugged into the wall, bypassing the charging base. So much for long-lasting, when I have laptops/smartphones/etc. with lithium-ion batteries that last upwards of 3-5 years and still function. Have submitted a support request to Eufy to see if they will back up their "All quality-related defects on items sold directly by eufy are covered by an extensive warranty." Not getting my hopes up and in the meantime, I'll start looking for a real Roomba.

R68:	I bought this to maintain the 1st floor between real cleanings with a proper vacuum. I am starting to think it was a waste of money. Disclaimer - this is a household with pets. Our regular vacuum is a Bissell Pet Hair Eraser, and dog hairs DO NOT get tangled on the brush. This RoboVac, unfortunately, has a plain old rotating brush and bristles, and dog hair gets caught in it - a lot. Every 2-3 run times, you'll notice that the tray is either empty or close to empty, and that is a sign that the brush needs to be removed, pair of scissors brought out, and you need to have a go at the brush and remove all the hair that gets stuck on it. After using the Bissell vacuum with the no-tangle brush, this is a real PITA. I think I could get over it if it did other things I bought it for well, but it doesn't. Scheduling - I tried twice, and it scheduled only for the next run - didn't have any luck running it on a daily schedule. In all honesty, it would not make a difference anyway, because... Navigating - it get stuck all the time, in the same spots. We have hardwood and tile, with a 4x6ft low-pile shag rug. It can get on the rug, but it gets stuck on the edges of it all the time. It gets stuck when it goes under the sofa and tries to go on the rug. It gets stuck under the front of the fridge.It gets stuck around the bottom of the dishwasher. It "humps" my end table for as long as you let it - table base is low and circular with one tube going up from the middle of it, and Goofy keeps humping and going in the circle around it seemingly forever. Yes, we named it Goofy because the name of the manufacturer looks like Gufy instead of Eufy, and because it gets stuck constantly. I bought this to help between regular cleanings, to schedule it and have the house clean when I get home, but it requires so much user interaction, it makes it useless. So, hair get stuck in the bristles, I can't schedule it and it gets stuck all the time. On top of this, going over my rug after "Goofy" has completed its run with our Bissell produces so much hair, I'm not sure why I even bother. I think this would be great for household without pets, and for floors with single level surface only - no rugs or anything raised. But it doesn't work well at all for our needs. I should have returned it while the return window was open..

R69:	I purchased this vacuum in June of 2017. It worked great and did as advertised. However, in October of 2017 it stopped working. After working with Eufy's support they determined it was defective and sent a replacement unit. I was extremely pleased with the support I had received. I had even recommended a friend to purchase one, which he did. Then in April of 2018 the vacuum started making a loud grinding noise. The noise would disappear when removing the main brush, and a replacement brush did not resolve the issue. I reached back out to support, and once again they sent me a replacement. Slightly annoying that I've had to replace it twice, but at least support was helpful and sent us a replacement. Just over 3 months later the 3rd Robovac we've had failed again. Now it states the main brush is stuck, when it turns no problem manually. At this point Eufy support came back and said they will not be sending any more replacements as it is outside of the warranty. This was infuriating, as we never had a working Robovac for more than 5 months. This product is garbage, and while their support was helpful at first, I can no longer say anything positive about them. Not taking care of a customer that has had multiple defective products is borderline unethical. I will never purchase nor recommend another Eufy product. UPDATE - Support has reached out to notify us that they will now replace our latest defective vacuum, so I have updated my review from a 1 to 3 star. Hopefully this one lasts.

R76:	This was our first robot vacuum and we loved it at first. It does and OK job on our hardwood floors but you will still have to manually vacuum every once in a while. We had to find creative ways to block it off in certain areas because it does not have any type of boundaries. It has a problem picking up larger objects like dog food, rice or larger crumbs. It knocks the larger objects out of the way with the brushes instead of pushing it to the middle where it is picked up. Our true problems started just after the 1 year warranty expired. Our side brush stopped working. We tried cleaning the motor and brush assembly, we even tried removing the brush but it never worked reliably after that. Then the motor suddenly wouldn't ever stop even when it was on the dock charging, we had to turn the unit off to stop the motor. Now the motor doesn't work at all. Customer support was no help, they do not offer a replacement motor. They just wanted me to buy an entire new vacuum. I'll find a better way to spend my money next time.

R77:	Ordered this product just over a year ago, and was amazed at it's initial performance. After the first month I noticed that it needed to be rescued more and more often. Most of the time it was under a couch, chair or table. Fast forward to about the 6 month mark, and it is all but useless on carpet. The vac now only spins in circles and goes into distress mode whenever it touches carpet. Move it back to the hardwood floor and it works like a dream again. This vac does a great job around the edges of a room if you have hardwood flooring, but if you have any carpet or area rugs be prepared to hear it's incessant beeping. Replacement brushes and filters are east to find, and are relatively inexpensive. If you have only hard wood, or tile floors this vac will do a pretty good job. The battery life is pretty impressive, but it has never found it's way "Home" to recharge. In hindsight not a great purchase.

R78:	The roller brush motor on this vacuum began failing about 14 months after purchase so it was out of warranty. After going through all the trouble shooting(cleaning hair out of roller brush bearings, running without roller brush and getting the same error code), I contacted eufy support about getting a replacement motor or out of warranty service. They flatly refused. So now I have an otherwise perfectly good vacuum with a bad motor that I am unable to repair. Motor replacement would be a simple procedure. I have had the vacuum apart multiple times to clean the motor. If you buy a Eufy product, just know that it is disposable. There are no replacement parts. If it breaks out of warranty, your only option is to throw it away. I really wish that I had bought a Roomba. It would have been more expensive initially, but I would have been able to get replacement parts. There is a reason these things are so cheap. You get what you pay for.

R79:	Updated Review: Originally I gave this vacuum 4 stars (down from 5...), but I have now changed it to 1 star. I have owned this vacuum for 4 months now and STILL can not buy replacement filters. Only in the past week have replacement side brushes and rollers been made available. Since filters are supposed to be replaced once a month (as per the manual), this seems like a major oversight by Eufy. Original Review: This is an excellent vacuum. I have hard wood floors with mats all over (in front of the doors, kitchen sink) as well as an area rug (typical carpet, not shag) in the living room. This vacuum does very well cleaning all of it. It runs over the mats and rarely pulls up the edges. I've had this vacuum for a couple months now and run it at least once per week and it has only pulled up the edge of a mat once. But it never stopped the Robovac. The only issue I have with this vacuum is you can not get replacement filters or side brushes for it. So for a while I guess I'll have to clean the filter with water, but that won't last forever. Considering the build quality of the vacuum and the time and energy it saves me from not having to sweep and vacuum the house, I'd love to give the Robovac 11 5-stars. But considering that Eufy must be selling a ton of these and has no way for it's customers to replace the consumable parts of the vacuum, I can't give it the full 5 stars.

R80:	UPDATE 5/1/2017: I wanted to write an update to my review based on my experience with resolving issues with the RoboVac through Eufy's customer support. I have to say, if you're not sure if this will work for you - ORDER IT ANYWAY. I place several *hundred* orders a year through Amazon, mainly because I want to be protected for larger purchases with a simple-to-use return process and policy (which Amazon delivers on). However, this is the first experience I've had with *proactive* direct-connect customer support from Eufy. THey reached out immediately upon my initiation of the return, responded to my messages within hours, if not minutes, and literally had a "tell-us-what-will-make-you-happy-and-we'll-do-it" attitude. I have never updated or come back to report on a review, and the whole experience just shocked me and was such a nice surprise to accompany Amazon's already strong customer service. It made me so much more confident in their products, even though the RoboVac didn't work out for me, I ended up with the Cordless stand-up vacuum instead. I even ended up ordering the Eufy wireless body scale that I forgot I had added to my cart a while ago and was on the fence with - simply because I felt so much more confident that it would be handled well, should anything go wrong. ______________ Ugh - I wanted so badly to be in love with this. So far, all the other Eufy products I have are FANTASTIC! This one just needs an upgrade in a few areas to make it effective and competitive. The suction is nearly ineffective unless you use the "max" button, but there doesn't appear to be a permanent way to make the device apply maximum suction at all times (such as scheduled cleanings, etc.) - it appears to return back to the default level. (I'm assuming this is to conserve power). Definitely +1 star to agree with what all the other reviews have said - even at max, the unit is incredibly quiet. It just doesn't clean effectively. I have hardwood floors and when I sent the unit under my couch (where there is a visible layer of dust) it barely made a dent. In fact, the wheels seemed to pick up more dust off the floor than the brushes themselves. (attached are pics) Returning to Amazon until there is a new updated release or fixes.

R81:	For the first 6 months I was smitten with this vacuum. Loved it!!! Then at around 6 months of use, it kept stopping and giving 2 beeps. No matter what I did, it would stop every 10 minutes, give or take. Kind of defeats the purpose of turning it on while away at work. After trying many suggestions, I called customer service. I swear the guy helping me was a young teenager. He told me to bang on the front of it at which I told him I had done that. He then told me to bang it harder. That was ALL I got. After another 6 months of using it while I was at home so I could restart it when needed, I emailed customer service to see what to do. They replied that if I purchased another they would give me $30. off. Not to sound ungrateful but I saw $30.00 off coupons on some of their products for everyone. I loved it so much that I am going to give it one more try and purchase a second one. I hope this one works longer than 6 months.

R84:	I wanted to love this vacuum! I couldn't believe how awesome the reviews were for it and figured that robot vacuums have FINALLY gotten good enough (and affordable enough) that we should purchase one. It just didn't live up to the hype and was so useless since it required a lot of human help. Bad: Maybe our Eufy is defective... but it would give a 3 beep error tone about every 5-10 minutes of vacuuming. This error (according to the manual) says that Eufy is hanging off a ledge or is trapped. This was never true! A lot of times he would just be in the middle of our living room floor, or near a wall - always in areas that would be very easy to continue cleaning. To prove a point, I would hit his start button after he gave the error tone, and he would start back up continuing to do business as usual. Ultimately this is why I returned him. If he can't vacuum without constant help and supervision from me, he doesn't have a purpose. I might as well be vacuuming myself instead of chasing him down to hit his start button every 5-10 minutes. The other thing that I really couldn't get over was the random cleaning patterns. I love good carpet lines, and Eufy makes it look like minions cleaned your house. I was a little embarrassed when people came over because people don't assume you have a robot vacuum and just look at you funny :) If your OCD about that stuff, wait until more tech comes along or go buy a fancy one. I just hadn't realized this was his cleaning method until we bought him. There really wasn't any reviews that mentioned this. Good: There were some really nice things about this model that we loved. I hate vacuuming and just the idea that we could buy an affordable robot to do it for us is so dreamy! Also, we have dog and this vacuum is SO easy to clean the hair out of! The brushes come apart so easily- no tools or muscles needed. The remote is also a nice touch. I loved being able to control the vacuum to go to areas that had been bothering me. I loved having it on a timer and the idea that it was vacuuming the surface area dust everyday without any help from me. Ultimately, I think we're starting to get there... maybe next Christmas there will be better options in this price range. I just can't seem to figure out why everyone else specifically "loves eufy" so much.

R103:	This little vacuum worked great for the first year. Great for keeping down the general amount of dust and hair on the floor. However, after about a year, the navigation and battery-life began to deteriorate. At first the robot would almost never run into furniture, but would slow to a stop before changing directions. Now, it hits everything at full speed before bouncing away. Battery life is down to about 30-40 minutes and it is no longer able to find its docking station. The initial performance of this product, especially considering the price, easily gets 4.5-5 stars. But a 1-1.5 year period of usefulness makes this a borderline disposable product, so I have to reduce its rating.

R122:	Disappointment OVERALL: 2.5/5 Marginal at best. I really wanted to like this after reading over the reviews, and in about 5 years, these robotic vacuums will be awesome, but they're not there yet. It does a decent job at picking up dust, but there are major downsides, and you won't want to keep this for more than a few months. I am returning mine to Amazon. Make sure you go through the reviews and try to weed out fake reviews on the website. Note there are external websites that do this for you if you do a search. PICKING UP DUST: 3.5/5. It works about as well as a small hand held vacuum that you take around to pick up small messes. So, you won’t get much power on anything besides a hardwood/tile floor or very thin carpet. It does work on standard carpets, but not that well. Definitely a step down from a standard vacuum cleaner, and no comparison to a steam cleaner. You will be surprised at the amount of dust it can gather though. BATTERY: 3/5. Advertised for 1.5-2 hours? The BEST I got was an hour. Expect that to decrease over time as the battery dies RECHARGING: 1/5. It takes 3+ hours to get the full charge. TIMER MODE: 2/5. This almost never automatically works for me and I followed instructions perfectly. MANEUVERABILITY: 2.5/5. It is just so dumb. The random mode will take it all around the room, but it will go into a wall at an angle, then it will turn 5 degrees, go forward, then bump into the same wall, then turn 5 degrees, then repeat and repeat. Then it will sometimes do an about face and go elsewhere. There is no rhyme or reason to where it goes. MODES: 2/5. There is an auto mode, a spot cleaning mode, a periphery cleaning mode, etc. Auto is the go-to, and it is no good. Spot cleaning is pointless – just get your vacuum cleaner if you spilled something. Periphery mode is good, unless you want the actual room cleaned. RETURNING TO STATION: 1/5. It returned for me in 10% of cases. And that was almost always in the periphery cleaning mode. When it leaves the charging station, it usually pulls the station along with it a little bit, making it hard to dock later. VALUE: 2/5. At $180, this is not worth it. It’s better than the competitors, but not by much. But just wait for a few years when these things are <$100 and have better software. PHOTOS: one of the photos is how much dust I got in a few hours of cleaning a 14 x 12 room. It’s a lot! Another photo is how I would randomly find the Robovac – sometimes almost near the recharge station, usually NOWHERE CLOSE. 3rd photo is how the vacuum pulls out the charging station.
	S1:	Disappointment OVERALL: 2.5/5 Marginal at best.

Next robot worked fine for a couple months, then one day I came home to it sitting in the middle of the living room, as if it ran out of charge on the way back to the dock. Picked it up and put it back on the dock, thinking it just needed to charge. Next day, it went to start up at its scheduled time, but immediately gave its error beeps instead. Thinking perhaps I hadn't set it quite right on the charger, I turned it off and resettled it there. Unfortunately, that wasn't it, and even after letting it charge for another day, and doing several hard resets, it still wouldnt run. Frustrating, but the customer service has been truly excellent. Quick response, willingness to quickly ship replacements - really feels like the company makes it a high priority to ensure these things are working. Even after two haven't worked, this excellent service as well as the apparently good build quality of the things makes me think it's worth trying another. If they robots were really breaking down often for everyone, no way they could afford to keep this level of service up!

R173:	2nd robovac, I bought this to replace Neato XV sig-pro after 2 years of use battery and long standing dust bin glitches finally wore it out. Pro: super quiet, good suction (just as good as Neato), big easy to use waste bin, 3 layer air filter. Con: stupid, the thing has no rhyme or reason to its cleaning "pattern" making it overly inefficient both in time and cleaning. Scheduling sometimes it runs when it's supposed to, sometimes it doesn't, lately it's been staring randomly in the middle of the night. No screen or digital feedback remote not very effective. Neato was easier to schedule and gave better feedback so you knew what it was doing or needed. Neato's pattern may have spoiled me, it is why I choose over Roomba as my first robovac, it was very logical and efficient, Eufy is entirely the opposite. Doesn't go over area rugs as well as Neato. Have to update this after about 8 months this thing is just awful. It is attracted to people and the dogs we have moved through the room and it will essentially follow you from area to area and ride around your feet. Its is almost like the thing tries to get stuck, it runs so unorganized it's just terrible. The scheduler no longer works for schedule it to run. I'm going office space on it and throwing it away just not worth the aggregation. Really regret this purchase I researched the heck out of it too.

R204:	FINAL UPDATE: I bought a Neato Connected and it is SENSATIONAL. It completely maps your home each cleaning with LIDAR. Works in no light, vacuums every square inch of my floor plan and closets, then returns to base 100% of the time. I have a lot of sq ft, so it cleans til low on batt, returns for a charge, then picks up exactly where it left off. It has a full brush and EXCELLENT suction. A M A Z I N G! Perfect vac UPDATE: After living with the Eufy for 10-15 cleanings, the conclusions are quite clear, and none were never described in any of the many writte/youtube reviews I researched before buying. They are: the Robovac (and all the competition) must be within about 15 feet of the charging base, and facing it, when it gets low on battery, or the chance of it finding its base is inversely proprtional to your house size beyond that small arc. There are no other factors, because movements are random and it has no awareness of position. This is such a critical point that I can't believe none of the (100s?) of vac reviews I read ever mentioned it. Armed with the knowledge that there is no position awareness, or radio homing, or anything that could actually work, that makes a buying decision quite easy: If you have a simple floor area of say, 750 sq ft or less with a clear view of the base, a robot vac will work reliably for you as advertised. If you have more that floor area or it is complex, then the chances of the vac blindly wandering back into that arc, the base before i it dies, drops precipitously with more sq footage. So the obvious, cost-effective answer is to add more charging bases. Why this is not discussed in any of the product ads I've seen is beyond me. The are more expensive vacs with some primitive mapping functions, but reviews are so so, and frankly, once you understand the general stupidity of these bots, the much cheaper and more reliable solution is going to be a multi-base solution. The bases look and feel like they should retail for under $10. So all that said, it appears the Eufy line does not sell additional bases, but other visually near identical bots do. The iLifes and the Deebots sell bases for $25 each. So I took a chance and bought a base for an iLife and deebot to see if it would work with Eufy, but no luck. Today Eufy left a comment to contact them, suggesting they might send an additional base for "my situation" (meaning: I live in a full scale house). Nice of them, but I would need at least two more, and this info should be in the product description of all vac bots. So the answer is this: if you have a house without a continuous line of site to a charging base, buy a bot that sells additional bases. Its a much more cost effective solution than a gold plated bot, and is surely more reliable. ---------- 3rd UPDATE: Unfortunately, even after Eufy proofing my entire 1st floor, he bot keeps finding new ways to get stuck. It's almost like its real intelligence is fightingy efforts. It rarely completes a cleaning without: 1) getting hung up, or 2) randomly being too far away when return to base mode kicks in, too close to dying. Great try, but it just doesn't work automatically which is the main point. Small floorplans where the base is always in and few sharp corners would have fewer issues. 2nd UPDATE: This bot apears to be identical in every way to the Deebot N79, which is $20 cheaper and adds a wifi link in addition to the identical remote. It also appears to be an exact match with the iLife A4, which is also cheaper. UPDATE: Relocating the base in my largest room, plus blocking common jam areas (only a few nooks) has increased auto-docking chances to around 30%. The only reason auto docking improved from near 0% to 30% is because the probability of being in or near the lafgest room, when low power docking mode kicks in, is about 30% based on square feet. I think the Robovac 11 would work MUCH better if it auto-docked at about half power instead of 5-10 minutes from dead. Cleaning is still a little better than expected, but if you have a large or complex floor plan, you probably need a smarter/mapping robot vac. upgrading to 3 stars. ----------------------------- I've only had the RoboVac for two days, so I hope to update this review with a better overall experience. At first I was disappointed, then kind of ok with the purchase, then disappointed again. First impression: the vacuum pattern seemed very random, and my 2400 sq ft downstairs is quite complex. The combination of the two makes for sporadic cleaning and a generally confused robot. Next impression, considering the reasonable long battery battery life and cleaning time, the Eufy seemed to achieve descent coverage. I figured, if it runs each night, it'll work. It does pickup an amazing amount of dirt. With several cats, it fills the internal container in one use, no complaints, hopefully that will get better with time. Don't expect it to deep clean your carpets, its mostly a surface sweep, but it vacuums better than I expected from a crawling disk. Unfortunately, mostly negating my starting to like it better ofr cleaning utility, the bot has yet to relocate its charging dock, and so it winds up beeping help after every attempted cleaning. The roaming pattern seems to have no intelligence at all, and even when it has direct line of sight to its charger, it still fails to dock before dying. Don't know if this purchase is going to work out, considering returning for a pricier/smarter model. If you have a straightforward floor plan, I think it would work a lot better.

R232:	My Robovac 11 is OK, but I expected a lot more, even from a low end robot vacuum. The vacuum power feels a little too weak with the brushes comparatively too strong, so often times the vac just bats dust or fluffies around the home. Unless debris winds up right underneath the Eufy, the debris can often just wind up getting kicked out from the backside as it moves on. The remote control is admittedly cool, but I wound up having to use it frequently because the robot tends to have difficulty leaving the starting area, and especially moving between rooms, or even semi-divided open areas (it has trouble passing my couch, TV, and coffee table to get to the kitchen, so it winds up going back and forth over the same area rug repeatedly). The vac is also prone to getting stuck with laundry (a given with robot vacs), sliding doors (not cool), tall soft edges (it dug into then couldn't escape the side of my Jaxx bean-bag sofa), and has troubles with table + chair areas (sadly also expected). RoboVac handles edges with a few questions. In some cases, it approaches the edge, then turns away from it while still about 3 inches away. In other cases, it does a little creative maneuver with a bump rotate and move back into it...bump approach, but the logic seems to prefer going in one direction over another, and there's no button to trigger it, so to clean some edges I just had to repeatedly tell it to run into the wall, and in one or two cases I got so frustrated I had to pick it up and put it in the right spot. The rollers and side brushes seem ok in the short term maintenance-wise, but the filters feel like they fill up really fast, particularly if you're on any kind of carpet. You really have to empty the dust bin and clear the basic "lint" filter every single time the vac runs. I feel like clever design could have allowed the HEPA filter to be double, or perhaps even tripled in surface area with very little cost impact, thus allowing more suction power to make it through to the ground, and a more durable consumer product with slightly higher costing supplies costing everyone significantly less to ship (in total). All in all, I feel like it does make my life a little easier, but it takes a lot of looking after. If playing with gadgets is your thing, this may be up your alley. I believe the most important improvements that could be made are with area mapping logic, sensor logic, and filter design (which can enhance suction/overall cleaning power). Or just get a maid.

R243:	I loved, loved, loved this little guy for the first two months I had it. (I’ve had it six months now.) Amazing how it zooms around and under to suck up stuff. Using it 3-4x/wk has kept the floors and rugs cleaner overall, and the house is less dusty. It definitely slows down on areas that are all carpet, like the bedrooms, so I don’t use it as much as I should. I love that it will go under the bed no problem though. The reason I took away two stars: 1) there is a rubber flap that I guess help push dirt into the dustbin. Mine started to break off one side after about three weeks and by the sixth week, I had to snip off half of the flap because it was just dragging on the floor. I guess I would have to special order a whole new yellow bracket just to get a whole rubber flap. I don’t want to do that already. 2) About 8 weeks in, I turned on the little guy and let him roam. A few minutes later, I smelled POO. I tracked it down and it was coming from the Eufy. Apparently, my puppy had a (rare) house accident and the Eufy decided to scoop it up. Yup. Fresh poo all over the inside, brushes, and in the tread of the wheels. And then spreading it across the floor as it went on its merry way. I carefully and painstakingly cleaned every nook and cranny, ensuring everything was dry before I ran it again. It still works, but the sensors aren’t quite as keen as they were before. There’s much more bumping into things and getting stuck on things that weren’t a problem before. I keep the Eufy very clean, and have noticed the sensors improved a bit over time. But they’re just not like they were at first. I would have thought they’d have seen poo as too big to try to sweep (even if it was little puppy poo). Now when I run it, I do a quick survey to ensure the pup hasn’t left another surprise before Eufy does his chores.

R284:	Wanted to love it!!! Have been waiting for a long time to buy one. Read reviews on The Sweethome website and this was their fav after a lot of testing. But the battery didn't last as long for me and it could not get the corners. It did a great job of what it did pick up, a really great job but for more than $200 I guess I looked forward to more. I wish it completed a room in a very organized pattern from one end to another. But it bounces around the room without any definite path. R309:	I have never owned a "robo-vac" of any kind so I have no reference point for personal comparisons. I'll simply relay my brief but dismal experience. I placed the charger base in my kitchen (hardwood floor), nearby the carpet border with my living room. When I start the vac, it backs out, drives across the open area and immediately ran into a nic-nac shelf. It backed up and "maneuvered" around the obstacle and then proceeded onto the carpet. I don't have long carpet but the vacuum struggled mightly to drive around on it. It even just stopped moving completely and started beeping at me. I carried the unit back to the charger and tried again. This time, it started the exact same way running into the shelf, driving around, but it successfully traversed the carpet for about 10-15 minutes before getting stuck under a rocker-recliner. Ugh! I carried it back to the charger and tried again, this time I was forcing it to stay in the kitchen area by blocking it at the carpet edge. I watched it scurry around my kitchen floor and was very disappointed as I watched it fling the small bits of dry cat food that were on the floor. Next, I watched as it rammed into the cat's water dish and sloshed water all over the floor. Finally, it drove onto the heater grate in the kitchen and got stuck and was unable to move - it was "high centered" on a standard heater duct grate. I turned it off and carried it back to the kitchen table to pack this mobile trash heap back into the box and send it back. For what it's worth, it did seem to pick up a decent amount of dirt out of the carpet in the 15 minutes it was actually vacuuming the carpet. I can't say the same thing for the hardwood floor. Maybe it would have done better had it not got stuck on the air grate. The amount of time spent babysitting would be better spent just getting out my Dyson and vacuuming myself.
