R313:	The Eufy 11 is as good as these robot vacuums get. Sit back and let it do all the work. It does a good job of cleaning both low pile carpet and hard floors (wood/tile/marble). Easy to empty bin and handy remote control. So why only 1 star? Well, as is not uncommon on any appliance, there are parts that need occasional replacement such as the side rollers, filter, and main roller (all very reasonably priced IF AVAILABLE). Eufy sells more robot vacs than anyone yet there are no, and I repeat no accessories available for purchase either through Amazon or directly through Eufy. Sans the ability to buy replacement parts, this unit is not a wise purchase. Without working rotating side brushes, this unit is worthless. If I were a betting man, I'd say the company is just selling out their stock of this model, not manufacturing the accessories for it, and will introduce a newer, updated model in short order. Mine's going back this week for a refund,

Also you may notice that it gets stuck easily in small spaces or under the donning table and makes lots of attempts to get out doing the same over and over. Seems like the algorith that controls the movements is poorly designed. On the other hand, the suction is amazing and this together with the rotating brush makes a great job cleaning hard floors and carpets. My Wife was actually loving it but since we started facing the issues we are really disappointed with the product. Update: I have returned and bought a second one, ans still having the same issue. It stops without any alert or presenting an apparent issue. Still liking it because it keeps all floors very clean but we need to keep and eye on it. Returned after getting 2 units with same issues.

R321:	UPDATE: After posting this review, customer service reached out to me and sent me a replacement RoboVac 11 free of charge. The new unit continues to function as expected ~2 months after receiving it. While this does not speak directly to the RoboVac 11, it does reinforce the fact that Eufy stands behind their product. I am extremely displeased with this product and the service that Eufy customer support provided to date. I purchased the RoboVac 11 in March 2017 and it stopped working in April of 2018, approximately 2 weeks after the 1-year warranty expired. We do not have pets and only ran it once ever couple weeks across 20% carpet and 80% hardwoods. It was lightly used at best. Similar to other reviews, the vacuum now gives an error as if something (a motor or brush) is stuck and therefore no longer functions. All spin with no obvious signs of increased friction. After contacting customer support, i was told that there was nothing they could do regarding replacing the device, and when I inquired about options to replace one or more parts, they indicated that was not possible and sent me a generic youtube video explaining how to do a basic brush cleaning. With a $200 price point, i would expect far better reliability and improved customer service for this type of product. I am extremely disappointed with Eufy and will be hesitant to purchase a Eufy product again after the negative experience with the product and customer service.

R353:	One star for the product, 5 stars for customer support. I'm so bummed that this product doesn't work long because when it does work, it works great. I even suggested a few friends get this product (sorry, friends). I use this RoboVac in about 500 square feet with laminate flooring and a few small rugs. I did not get this small vacuum to take the place of a more powerful upright vacuum, but I used it a few times a week to help control the amount of god hair in my house. However, in my experience, they only last a few months. I purchased my first RoboVac in October of last year, then in February, the unit stopped working. The power button would turn red and it would beep two times indicating that the side brushes were stuck. I tried cleaning the entire unit and replaced the brushes, but it still wouldn't clean. I contacted customer support, and the next week I had a new RoboVac. Well, here I am just 4 months later and I am having the same problem. I once again contacted consumer support and they sent me a return label so that I can receive a refund. Hopefully that goes through. Maybe it's just bad luck to run into the same problem twice, but it's enough to look at other options. I would be hesitant to purchase from them again, and I hope that they can work on these kinks so that their products last longer.

GOOD: 1) Setup is easy 2) It's very quiet 3) Does well on hardwoods 4) Hit sensors do a much better job than my Roomba so it doesn't bang into as much furniture. BAD: 1) The scheduling seems off. I've got it set for 1:00 a.m. but I'll see it start later in the afternoon (I've verified the clock is correct) [Update: 4/27 - This has been corrected]. 2) Just won't work on carpet. I would classify my carpet as 'decent.' It is essentially one or two steps above builders grade. Update 4/27: We ended up moving this to a floor with no carpet and it works really well. It has great suction and is easy to clean. If you have only hardwoods, I definitely would recommend. I still could not recommend if you have carpet. Another note: Eufy Support is top notch. R369:	This is a solid 3 star because it largely performs its vacuuming well and is a great deal for the price. I have a dog that really sheds which means I would have hair on the floor and dust bunnies within a week, and this definitely prevents that and keeps the floor nice and clean. It loses points because the main reason someone is buying a robotic vacuum is to let it clean automatically, and this device can't really do that. First, it needs alexa or an app integration. You're at work, you decide that tonight you're hosting for the game, but you have no way to order the vacuum to vacuum. That's kind of unforgivable for a robotic vacuum, you know? It comes with a standard IR remote, but there's no way to non-locally order a cleaning. It either needs to be pre-scheduled or there is none. Eufy, if you're listening, I highly recommend an app and alexa for the next version. Second, unlike some other vacs there is no way to prevent it from vacuuming an area without physically blocking it off, which means any exposed wire could get swept up (and the suction is indeed good) and tugged along and if you have deeper carpets (as I do for a welcome/entry mat) it can't handle them and will get stuck. This means you can't really schedule a cleaning, you either have to run it when you happen to be in the room so you can keep an eye (or an ear, listening for it getting stuck) out for it, or you have to "prep" the vacuuming area by removing/blocking the problem areas. I do not use the scheduling functionality because I need to roll my welcome mat before turning the vacuum on. That should not have to happen. Great vacuum, falls short in the automation realm. Good value for price. 3 stars.

R371:	I've owned a couple of Roombas so my review compares the Eufy to previous experience these devices. The good: Eufy has great suction - Better than my previous Roombas and cleans well. It manages to traverse area carpets well. It's much, much quieter than the Roombas as well. The bad: Eufy's logic is lacking in comparison to a Roomba and this results in the unit getting stuck in places it simply shouldn't get stuck. It has difficulty with chairs and will enter under a chair and be unable to exit. This morning, it got stuck under a chair that has openings of 14" and 15". A Roomba simply pivots around a chair leg to exit. It also became confused under a chair with a closed back. The opening in the front is over 21", so I'm unable to explain why the unit became confused and gave up underneath it. It also became stuck between a toilet and the wall in the master bathroom. It just kept banging into the wall and the toilet. The vac needs to be smart enough not to enter areas so tight it can't exit. I've seen reviews and answers to questions regarding its ability to deal with rugs that have fringe. We have a dining room carpet with 4" fringe and Eufy became stuck on it multiple times. We also noticed that it managed to pull out some of the fringe damaging the carpet. This is obviously unacceptable. This unit does not have any kind of virtual wall available to restrict it from an area, so there is no way to make it avoid the carpet. The number of times Eufy becomes stuck is variable, but its current record is 7. If I have to chase the vac around restarting it continually, it defeats the purpose of the device and I might as well get my Dyson out and vacuum. I really want to like this little vac, but its limitations are aggravating and he may be returning to the manufacturer.

R387:	The one I got would only run for 30 minutes on a full 24-hour charge. That could be a manufacturing defect and it's not the end-of-the-world. Where it cleaned, it seemed to do a good job, it's fairly quiet and seems to be solidly built. The other problem is that the fall avoidance algorithm can't be turned off. Why not? Not every house/room has stairs. The result is that in a room that has dark rugs, it gets to the edge of the rug and thinks it is seeing a potential fall and retreats. Which means that some areas of the floor get cleaned endlessly while the rugs get nothing. Eufy, don't let programming teams make decisions like this, they have tunnel vision. You need real people in real houses to evaluate your product and recommend design changes. Any step or stairway can be easily blocked, but if I have to pick up my rugs, I don't want your product. If it had cleaned properly, I would have exchanged it for another one, because overall, I think it is as good as a Roomba, maybe better.

R390:	So having 3 dogs and 2 cats in a 800 sqft home tends to bring about a lot of floating hair and over time a smell associated with having animals in your home. Finding constantly annoyed with the need to vacuum almost every day I decided to give the Eufy a try. I also had a refurbished Neato XV in the past and it was fantastic. Unfortunately one of the cat decided to pee on it and it ruined the Neato and made it smell beyond fixing.... Pros: -Great Battery life. Gets about 1.5 hours of run time before needed to be charged. -The holding bin is of the largest size you can currently get for these RoboVac -It has plenty of suction power and pics up hair stuck in the carpet you will generally not even notice. Plus floating hair balls have been cut down to almost not existent. -The filter is very good it is much easier to clean then my Neato XV was. -It operation is fairly quite compare to the Neato that I previously had. -The build quality is nice. -short height allowing it to fut under low standing furniture. -The controller is nice but I never used it other then to set the Eufy up for the first time -Easy to disassemble for cleaning on a bi-weekly basis. Cons: -It gets stuck constantly. Vents in floor, in corners, forcing its self under furniture. Luckily it is easy to restart with your foot by pushing the big power button on top. The beeping noises it makes are not too annoying when stuck. -The sensors do get covered up quite easily with hair and will cause it to just stop in the middle of the room. This should be fixed. -It has almost no intelligent cleaning pattern, bouncing off walls to figure its way around the house. -Not very good at cleaning wall edges. Get luckly that it blows hair off the edge of the wall so it can collect it later... Comparing this to the Neato I had. I really miss the Neato. It was easy to predict that the Neato would clean the whole house roughly the same way every time with very little assistant needed. I can't afford a new Neato and this was a great deal at the time for $175. At that price I would recommend the Eufy but I would recommend the Neato any day over the Eufy at the same price. Hope this helps.

R391:	I've been waiting several years to buy a robot vacuum, but was always underwhelmed by performance and price. When the New York Times reported that the relatively inexpensive Eufy had bested Roomba, I bought one at once. Sadly, it's clunky junk in my home. Others have cited its blinding weaknesses, so I will be brief in recounting them again. It gets hung up with regularity, and on the most mundane "obstacles." It cannot cross even the lowest thresholds. It refused to cross from my very thin carpeting (Flor system carpet tiles) to the hardwood floors. It acted like it was on the edge of a precipice. I expect it was because my floors and rugs are all dark. It never seemed to learn anything in its wanderings, even when I gently nudged it across thresholds or extricated it from its constant alarm conditions. Add to all this that it didn't pick up all that much. Terribly disappointed with this dud. Not worth the trouble at any price. June 21, 2017 addendum: To their credit, the Eufy folks expressed concern about my unmet expectations and asked if they could send me a free Eufy. I thought that odd as, even free, the product wouldn't do the job. But, who turns down free? What arrived surprised me. Instead of a robot cacuum, they sent a rechargeable upright vacuum. I already have a great upright vacuum by a well-known English maker of vacuums; hence my interest in a robot vacuum. "Great," I thought, "ANOTHER vacuum to store or give away." But, I tried it, and I have to say, it's great and so handy. Small, lightweight and cordless, it feels almost like a toy, but--and I say this as praise--it really sucks. It makes short work of picking up the crumps, dust, sand and debris of daily foot traffic. It's small enough to fit behind my bedroom door. It's a great little vacuum. Perfect for an apartment dweller and for light-duty cleanup. It doesn't change a thing in terms of the failures of the robot version, but it certainly makes me admire Eufy's customer care. Thanks for the great gift, Eufy!

R424:	Ive had this vacuum for a year now. I replaced a Rollibot vacuum when my husband broke it by snapping one of the side sweepers (thanks, hun) So I have some basis for comparison. Pros: Low profile. Can even get under the couches (barely) which is great so long as it finds its way back out again Large waste bin. Only ever need to dump it out once its done. Long battery life. Lasts hours. Cons: Cant handle pet hair. In addition to the sweepers theres a middle brush similar to a regular vacuum. This sucks (in the wrong way) for pet hair. It constantly needs to be cleaned out and pet hair gets trapped in the space between the brush and the bin. That big bin size I mentioned earlier? Useless because when clogged nothing makes it in there anyway. This machine has degraded fast. Now when I run it, it will constantly stop in the middle of the floor and beep like there's an issue. Best i can tell is its due to the hair clogging it. But even cleaning it out ends up giving me just a few minutes before I have to rescue it again. The point of these things is to let them run while you do something else. Instead i have to go press the button every minute or so just to get it to keep moving. It got to the point where sweeping manually was faster and less stressful. I'm finding myself really missing my Rollibot.

R426:	If you do not want cleaning to occur on a daily schedule/timer, then this will be a great vacuum for you. There is however issues with the scheduled cleaning function and it does not work after a period of time. For the first several months of using it I had no issues. I scheduled cleaning everyday at 8am. Then it started coming on later and later, almost like the clock was off. I verified it was not, then it started cleaning at 3am when it was set for 8am. Then it stopped cleaning all together. I could still manually start it and it would clean no problem. Problem is, I bought it to automatically clean every day, not to manually clean when I remembered to push the button. I will say the customer service is great! I emailed Eufy with my proof of purchase and within a few days I had a replacement item in route to me and they told me to keep my existing unit. The replacement unit worked well, but after a few weeks it was having the same problem with scheduled cleaning. I contacted Eufy again and they are going to issue a refund. Again, their customer service was great but the vacuum obviously has a bug that prevents scheduled cleaning from occurring over time. I am told their newer models don't have this issue, but I cannot verify that personally. The function of the vacuum is great, it works well and other than getting stuck a few times under a baby gate and on a big bath mat, it cleans very well. You cannot schedule daily cleanings reliability, so that is the only issue, but it is a major one for me.

R427:	Well I loved this little robo vac for the first 3 months. Just after the warranty expired it died. One of the front brushes stopped working, which made the entire machine stop. I did all I could (replaced the brush, cleaned the machine, etc.). I contacted customer support and they were willing to replace the machine. Great! Except they didn't have the same model and what I got instead was some lesser Eufy - which, frankly, is terrible. Whatever programming it has causes it to get stuck repeatedly where the first could successfully navigate, shorter battery life (likely because it is refurbished), and lastly it has little suction. So, while the first did a great job of sucking up pet hair (the number one reason for my purchase) the new one leaves it all behind. Basically I am back to just using my regular vacuum with the added pleasure of fishing the stupid Eufy out from wherever it got stuck overnight. So disappointed because this was an extremely expensive purchase and I got only 3 months use out of it. Sadly can't recommend.

R430:	Update to the previous review below, I have to give eufy credit and perhaps an extra star for the 11 for the response. The 11 itself is not a product for everyone I have found and they were quick to suggest giving the 30 a try. In retrospect I wish I had reached that conclusion from the start. The boundary strip feature found in the 30 turned out to be critical to making the experience effective. I gave up the hepa filter but I wasn't too concerned about that. I left a more detailed review of the 30 but the one bit of credit I will give is for eufy's efforts to track customer satisfaction. They do a remarkable job on follow-ups and seem genuinely interested in their customer's satisfaction. So again, the 11 wasn't the product for me but if you have a normal every day floor with no silliness going on or unusual changes in height/material it will likely get the job done. Best of luck! Pictured is the transition that causes us the most trouble. Overall this little device has worked 'alright'. It's been ok. Not impressive and at times annoying. It manages most bumps and challenges like carpet transitions well, but it gets stuck on other things like an errant flip flop or extension cord. It has a major problem with the door to our porch which has a small transition lip on the floor. It goes up the lip, hits the door, backs down, goes forward and up the lip, hits the door, goes down... makes a god awful racket in the process. "Buh dunk, buh dunk, buh dunk, buh dunk" for about 5 minutes before it moves on on its own or is told to go elsewhere. It doesn't handle pet hair well at all. It picks it up but I also have to pick it out of the brush regularly. All and all cleaning is acceptable but I guess I had hoped for more out of a modern "robot" vacuum.

R435:	I have had this vacuum, who we've lovingly nicknamed Eufy, for about 6 months now and have really gotten to know it. I have to say it's just okay. The other reason that I only give it 3 stars is because it gets stuck in a lot of places, so someone actually needs to be home when it's running-- it woudn't work for us to just turn it on before we leave the house -- we would for sure come home to Eufy stuck somewhere. My kids are becoming pros at going to "rescue" Eufy when they hear the familiar beep indicating that it is stuck, and we often have to go on "Eufy hunts" when we notice it hasn't returned to the home base and is stuck somewhere. I didn't expect to need this amount of effort and attention for a robot vac. But it is better than noting for us.

I've found it stuck on a floor board, on a heating grate, and a door sil, and on power cords. It's supposed to have all these fancy sensors but it seems to find a way to get stuck. The other strange thing is the amount of recommended room that the instructions want for placing the charger: it wants 36 foot square space blank space against a wall; six feet along a way and six feet out from the wall. That's a small room just for this thing to sit and charge. On the other hand, I was stunned when I emptied out the bin and found it full of debris. Who knew?! It does vacuum up a tremendous amount of dust. The Braava hardly ever got stuck. I could stick a dry swiffer cloth on it for dust and a wet siffer cloth for mopping and it would just go! However, it was not a vacuum so it couldn't do my area rugs.

R439:	I’ve had and used this vacuum for over a year, and it has made me clean and sweep the floor more than when I never had it. Reasons why you should just buy something else: 1. This vacuum does not clean the whole area, just one spot, wherever it wants really. No rhyme or reason why it goes where it goes. 2. It’s a PLANT BULLY. I have several plants in my home, some on the floor and some on plant stands. This vacuum will run into my plants over and over until they topple over and spill soil all over the place, then attempt to clean the soil, but instead spreads the soil all over the house. 3. If you forget and let it run too long it will remain where the battery died and you will have to bring it and manually insert it into the charging dock. 4. It likes to eat bathroom rugs. 5. It doesn’t always know how to find its way home to its charging dock. I’ve advised all my friends to invest in a better vacuum, not something like this, and now I’m telling you. Trust me, it’s worth it, in the long run.

R441:	Okay, don't know if I will show as verified, as I purchased on eBay from Ankerdirect to get 10% off. Received eufy with quick shipping from local outlet fulfilled by Amazon. I charged, flipped over to install the side brushes, and WHOH!, the main brush was full of crap and hairs!!! (see photo). USED! Should NEVER happen, ever! STRIKE ONE Emailed eufy and they quickly agreed to send RMA and issue a replacement. I made sure to ask for a NEW PRODUCT, NOT USED! They issued the RMA and I repacked into the Amazon mailer and when I tried to mail it there was insufficient postage!!! STRIKE TWO Went home, reprinted RMA, tossed one box and had to re-mail. GRRR. Replacement robovac shipped from Kentucky and took longer (BUT, USPS delivered on a Sunday!!) Maiden voyage: ziggged and zagged around, got stuck once (might have got unstuck if I waited), limped and found its base when tired. Did a good job and wife happy. We are waiting for the appropriate name to strike us for our new toy. So far, very happy with performance. Will update when tested further and change stars if it keeps up the good work. For Anker: 1. When the robovac needs to charge, have it cease the vacuuming function so it has plenty of power to get home. 2. Have a "full dust bin" warning or stop vacuuming and go home. We had a clean home, just vacuumed, but it still over-filled up in one session.

R447:	This was our first robotic vacuum and after hours of research we decided on the Eufy 11. I must say I was amazed at how well it worked! We continued to still use it with it only working half the time. Fast forward another 6 months and now this thing is so loud and obnoxious it is unbearable to us. At this point if we do run it when we leave it really doesn’t pick up anything and it’s basically a waste of time. My wife wants a new one and I’m not happy about having to buy a new one just a year later. I decided to look back to see exactly how long I’ve had it because I figured they had some sort of warranty and I have read good things about there customer service. Well wouldn’t you know I’m exactly 20 days past the one year warranty, just my luck! At the end of the day these are priced decent compared to some of the competition but if you have to replace every year it might be better to buy a more expensive one that last longer. Hopefully Efuy works out the issues with there vacuums because it was such an amazing product at first.

R457:	I wanted to love this vacuum so, so badly. After all, it came highly-reviewed for its price point, and in particular the main thing I needed it to do -- judiciously pick up loads of cat hair off a wood floor -- seemed to be one of its strong suits. Unfortunately, at least in my case, this has proven frustratingly untrue. While it seems mediocre to halfway decent at general vacuuming, I cant imagine a less efficient or effective robot when it comes to picking up pet hair on my hardwood floors, as it seems to prefer to just shoot the hairs out or spread them around vast stretches of my apartment, resulting in lengthy skid marks of compressed pet hair which I have to then pick up when the robot finally and mercifully turns off for the day. Finally, I would also mention that, while I knew I wasn't purchasing a particularly "smart" robot, I certainly didn't expect it to be this dumb. I absolutely cannot run the thing without close supervision, because it seems to obsessively return to the same spot in my living room dozens of times during its daily run cycle; a spot which has three metal-legged dining table chairs. It climbs these legs incessantly and gets stuck on them, resulting in me having to physically move the stupid thing across my apartment and restart it...20+ times a day. 30 seconds later, its back on the legs again. It seems almost as if I've paid 260 dollars for a drunk toddler to clean my apartment once a day, which is particularly maddening. I would certainly not buy this vacuum again, and I will avoid Eufy in the future.

R540:	I purchased a Roomba over 10 years ago and have dismissed robot vacuums until now. It was anything but smart, had terrible suction, and was relentless at cleaning one area of the living room while neglecting everywhere else. But now being blessed with kids and a larger floor plan, I started looking at robot vacuums again in hopes they have gotten smarter and more efficient. But I can’t justify spending $500+ on one so that’s how I landed on the Eufy RoboVac 11. The reviews are great, product looks good, and the specs were very promising. I also looked at the DeeBot N79 and have since tried it as well, and I’m debating on which to keep. Here’s why: We have a 1,700 square foot home and we do our best to keep random objects off the ground for a clear cleaning path. I’m very impressed with how much the RV11 picks up everyday (disgusting to think about too), and how well it navigates between hardwood, tile, and low-pile carpet. I’ve only used it with the full-auto setting and for the most part it is very thorough. I love walking into the bedrooms to see the RV11’s tracks on the carpet and seeing how much cleaner it is. It manages to navigate and bounce around the entire home with enough power to navigate back to it’s charging dock. So again overall we’re quite happy. But when I say bounce around, I mean it in the most noisy/stumbling/tripping/startling/drunken sort of way. Compared to the DeeBot N79 (which looks almost identical and can even share the same docks and remote), the RV11 acts like it’s drunk when going from room to room. The infrared sensors seem to be inferior to the N79 in that it still bumps into everything: dark colored furniture, bright colored baseboards, our feet, gray walls, etc. The Eufy RV11 is no ninja thanks to it’s clumsiness, though the unit itself is reasonably quiet. For this reason alone we are hesitant on keeping it. The Deebot N79 in comparison was $20 less at time of purchase, includes wifi, has an app that you can control the unit from, and the app also allows you to find your cleaning buddy if it gets trapped or stuck somewhere in the house. On top of this, the N79 looks sober and cautious in comparison to the RV11 as it pauses around objects and makes mini corrections around corners. To put it more into perspective, I feel comfortable letting the N79 roam the house while the kids are napping. The Eufy RoboVac 11? No way. The thought of the RV11 going down the hall knocking on walls and doors and waking up the little ones makes me want to ship it back right away or limit it’s use to times when the kids aren’t home. Unfortunate, because nap time is when things get done around here. But here’s the dilemma. Between the two, the RV11 has been superior in thoroughness and consistency. Like I mentioned earlier, the Eufy RV11 makes multiple passes in each room and barely leaves any untreated spots. And while the N79 is more meticulous around objects, it apparently suffers from attention disorder and looks like Dory as it cleans only a few spots before moving on to the next room. What’s even more frustrating is that when Dory (N79) returns to the room, it somehow manages to clean only the same spots again in slight variations and then moves on again. So would I recommend the RV11 over the N79? Yes, because it cleans well and while it could use a rehab program, it still remains functional and stumbles its way home to the charging dock. The N79 on the other hand may have the added bells and whistles with wifi, but if anything it performs just a hair better than my Roomba 10 years ago.
	S1:	I purchased a Roomba over 10 years ago and have dismissed robot vacuums until now.

	NerTag:	[O, O, O, O, O, O, O, O, O, O, O, O, O, O, O, O, O, O, O, O, O, O, O, O, O, O, O, ORGANIZATION, DATE, DATE, DATE, O]
R541:	Issue: As of right now, there is no way to get replacement parts for the "HEPA-style" filter and side brushes, both of which will need to be replaced. This is quite disappointing, as this is easily a 5-star product which a glaring omission. Doing a google search shows there are no replacement parts for sale for the Robovac 11, short of emailing Anker and asking to buy them directly, according to Anker's support forum (although who knows at what price). This is not an acceptable way to purchase replacement consumable parts in 2017. The parts really should be for sale on Amazon. However, as I wrote earlier, the vacuum is a 5-star product and I will update my review once replacement parts are more readily available. The story of a little vacuum that could: The suction on this thing is incredible. First, I vacuumed my floors with my upright vacuum before use (just to see if this little guy really could impress), moved all cords out of the way, and then let the Eufy go to work. My first impression was, "Wow. This thing is quiet! There is no way it is collecting anything off the carpet." But a quick inspection of the collection bin after 30 minutes of operation showed an embarrassingly large amount of chihuahua fur, dirt, and other little particles. So I emptied the bin and let it resume cleaning. When I noticed that the Eufy had made its way back to the charging station, I checked the bin again. More fur and dirt! Also, there were some medication tabletes I had dropped somewhere several months earlier! I'm not a dirty person, and am still blown away that this quiet little vacuum found some potentially toxic poisons and swept them up before my dogs could get to them. Impressed, I let the Eufy recharge. This does take quite a long time, but is in no way a deal breaker. The logo on the top of the vacuum pulses when recharging and goes solid when done. When it was fully charged, I thought to myself, "I wonder what else this little guy can find." More dog fur! More dirt! It just keeps finding it. Each time I empty the bin I'm astonished. And now, my floors have never looked cleaner. I can actually lay down on the carpet and not be covered in dog fur when I stand up. Bravo. Pros: - Best value for the price - Great suction - Incredibly quiet (I bet I could use this at 2:00 am and my condo neighbors would be none the wiser) - Lots of modes to choose from on the remote control - Programable for daily operation - When battery power is low, suction turns off and the vacuum makes it way back to the charging station (mine has always made it back) - Doesn't get stuck under chairs - usually it will just flip into "edge mode" and pivot around chair legs - Doesn't bother the dogs - Drop sensors prevent it from going down stairs, but aren't too sensitive for carpet-to-hardwood transition areas Cons: - Lack of availability of replacement parts (I'm looking at you, Anker), specifically replacement HEPA filters and side brushes (my first pair are already looking shabby after about a week of use) - The option to buy a replacement dust collection bin and main roller brush would be appreciated as well - currently, I've decided to just vacuum out the HEPA filter and foam cover when they get dirty and reuse them, but this is not a long term option - the unit does come with one replacement filter/foam cover and 2 replacement brushes, but I can't see the brushes lasting a long time - Unintelligent operation - it just goes in a straight line, bumps into something, turns, goes in another random direction - (this is not a terrible issue, it's just not as smart as other vacs that get a layout of the room and vacuum in straight lines, but there's no way I'm going to pay $900 for this feature **cough cough, Roomba, cough cough** - Collision detection is terrible - It seems to avoid lightly colored objects well, but runs right into dark objects. No damage, but it is annoying though, since it keeps making its way under my entertainment center and wrecks havoc with all the cords under there. Have a plan in place for issues such as these - I was using gray foam to hide the ugly mess of cords, but the Eufy sails right into it - Charging is slow but who cares? Program the vacuum to do its thing at 5 pm every day and forget it.

R542:	Multiple update review: Great bot...for the price. All I wanted was something to suck up the dog And cat fur that was creating tumble weeds in our house, without having to pull out the big vacuum. So this is Great. But beware, it's best on hard flat surfaces. It does get stuck on most of the rugs in our house, but sharp corners are an issue for it to clean, and it doesn't seem to really have a system/method to what it's doing, it just goes (update 7/8/17: yeah it's a really dumb bot). The spot clean function and the manual function are what i use the most, because they get the exact location i want. When I'm in my office, I'll set it to auto and let it run freely but will have to come grab it every now and then when it beeps (bc it got stuck on the high pile carpet). (update 7/8/17: i know what it gets stuck on, so i just block it off by curling the rug up under itself and creating a barrier, or I'll put something in it's way like shoes or pillows). There is a home function that is suppose to call the bot back to the charger, but i swear it has no idea where "home" is ...ever😄. Update October 21, 2019 - After 2 years Eufy is no longer working. not sure what the problem is.. I tried every possible troubleshooting method and replaced parts, but it just doesn't want to charge or run. I bought another robotic vacuum (the new fancy iRobot roomba) and regret spending money on this one in the first place. But it was good while it lasted and a great starter vacuum. So, take note that you'll probably only get 2 years out of a Eufy before you need to do some extra maintenance.

R544:	Having never owned a robovac, we couldn't pass up on a deal on this one. The price was fantastic and the reviews were overwhelmingly good. Keeping in mind we have not ever had a Roomba, our experiences and assumptions are not based on having used any other robovac. We set the thing up along a wall in our living room. Our house is a "ranch style" (long) house with kitchen then living room, then entry hall, then hallway down to the other end with doors to bedrooms, etc. So the Eufy is about in the middle of the house. Turned it on and told it to go. We observed it for about 30 minutes and we found out that it is really persistent about cleaning the kitchen and half of the living room. Over and over. We also found that it was unable to handle anything black. It's as though black is invisible to it. The Eufy would always get stuck on our black speaker stands. Try over and over and over to get through them, and would seemingly be stuck on them, but finally finds it's way off. Same with very dark wood pedestal easy chair. It's like it doesn't see it...it tried to go through it. We were trying to figure out if a robovac of this price range is smart enough to actually "map" the house or not, but it doesn't seem like it. When we tell it to go back to the dock, it acknowledges the command with a beep, but doesn't return home. Also, more than once, we find the light on top was red, and the vacuum motor was running in reduced speed mode, but no beeps and no indication why. Battery was fine. We put it back in the dock for a few minutes and told it to go clean again and it was fine. It did this 3 times. The manual doesn't say because most of the errors also have a beep sequence to them, which this did not. So, unfortunately, with the "black blindness" and the fact that it doesn't seem to clean the whole house, and the other issues we had, this might have to go back. We have no carpet in the main areas so this Eufy really shouldn't have problems, but it does when it comes to furniture and accessories that are black.

R545:	The RoboVac began having problems after less than 3 months of use. It now completely stops moving partway through any given cleaning session. I reached out to Eufy with a highly detailed written report on the problem, and they responded by giving me a soft refusal on following through with their "Long Warranty Time", unless, and ONLY IF I resort to a full video documentation of the entire cleaning process up to the point of failure. Given that I am a working professional with very limited time to myself, and that the device glitch appears to occur only after an extended period of cleaning (rather than near the beginning of a cleaning session), this is an unreasonably high burden as a condition on a warranty service request. I would not recommend this product to anyone. Edited as of 6/17/2017: Eufy has reached out and mailed me a replacement unit due to the issues with the previous one. I am giving them a tentative review adjustment to 3 stars (due to their correction in their warranty service). When I am satisfied that the new unit is functioning correctly, I may consider further review adjustments at that time.

R546:	UPDATE as of June 29: Eufy contacted me following my review below. They suggested some possible fixes and, when these didn't work, Eufy promptly refunded the purchase price. This is great customer service. Eufy explained that RoboVac 11 is an entry-level product that does NOT 'learn' the layout of your home. For the price, it's understandable that in 2017 RoboVac doesn't have sophisticated programming. Hopefully this will be remedied before long. The fact remains, as other recent reviews have shown, that Eufie can't find its way back to its base, can't maneuver on/off most carpets without getting stuck, can't figure out how to stop getting trapped under furniture. Nonetheless the vacuum does work well on wooden floors where there are few tight spaces. RoboVac didn't work for me, but given Eufy's good customer service I will be willing to try out future, more advanced models. When it works properly, RoboVac cleans the floor impressively. However it gets stuck every few minutes in or on rugs (even thin ones), tight corners, and under furniture. This happens every few minutes, requiring me to find the unit and 'free' it, defeating the purpose of an automatic cleaner. Worse, the software is rudimentary. It doesn't learn where problem areas are so it can avoid them. RoboVac does not know where 'home' is, so it has great difficulty returning to its base - mostly it doesn't make it without help. Also it starts up from the charging base on its own at random times, without being programmed to do so. Unfortunately I bought this unit just before taking an extensive trip and I didn't learn the product's shortcomings until after the 1 month Amazon return deadline had passed. Otherwise I would have sent this substandard product back. AVOID THIS PRODUCT. Don't make the same mistake I made.

R547:	Initial review: There is something wrong the automatic scheduling. I have repeatedly set the scheduled time for the RoboVac to run, and most of the time it does NOT run when scheduled. This largely defeats the purpose. I have also seen it start running randomly when it was NOT programmed to run. Extremely disappointed. Update 10-27: I'd give Eufy customer support 5+ stars if I could. They contacted me, explained why I was having the problem, and also offered an exchange or refund. Their support (Anker's generally) is exceptional. I still have mixed feelings about the Robovac 11 itself. If you turn the power switch off (almost always necessary to empty the dust bin, otherwise it tries to start running by itsefl), or if it gets stuck somewhere and runs out of power (a regular occurrence), the scheduled programming is gone. So basically I would have had to reprogram the schedule *every single day.* Not well designed in this respect. Eufy customer support arranged to send me a replacement, the newer 11+. Ironically, the very next day, the existing unit stopped working entirely. It just spun in place and went nowhere. The manual said this means the bumper is stuck and you have to free it so it can move. I did that, but to no avail. It was just plain kaput, after less than 2 months of ownership. Watching it work (when it was still actually working) was both pretty cool and maddening. It tools around, more or less randomly, but does a pretty good job cleaning up. On the other hand, it does not have programming that allows it to "learn," and it would get stuck and die in exactly the same places, day after day. Frustrating. I've also picked it up and "rescued" it when it was stuck, only to watch it immediately head right back to the same spot and get stuck again-- over and over. I'm guessing people's experience depends a lot on their space and how many places where it can get stuck, wedged under a chair or couch, etc. Update 11/4: Eufy 11+ is definitely an improvement. More power, better designed dust bin, and unlike my previous Eufy 11, it is not getting stuck constantly. So far, losing the programmed start time has not been a problem, probably because it is not getting stuck and running out of power all the time, and because you can empty the dust bin without having to turn off the power switch. Docked a star because the first unit had so many problems and because it doesn't "learn" the layout of your space and location of obstacles-- but probably the best value in a robo vac today. Update 10-2018: Final verdict, this is just more trouble than it's worth. The programmed schedule *never* seems to stay programmed, and it just seems to start a cleaning cycle at whatever random time it decides, generally at the most inconvenient time for me. I turned it OFF so wouldn't have to deal with it, and it still emits loud beeping sounds at random intervals, even when docked in its base and turned OFF. I just love getting woking up at night because it decides to beep loudly at some totally random hour, for no reason I can figure out. I generally love Anker products and support, but I would not buy this again.

R548:	UPDATE: Well, the love affair is over. After six months of light usage it is giving me an error code for the drop sensors. I have cleaned, recleaned and cleaned them again and frankly they weren't dirty in the first place as I wiped it down after each use. It has done a wonderful job and I was very happy with it, but apparently there are longevity issues and it isn't worth what it costs for such a short usage period. I would not have purchased this had I known that the life of one of these as stated by the company is only 18-24months if you are lucky and get a perfect unit. Don't purchase it, it just isn't worth the gamble on how long it will work. I have had this for a month now and I must have got a good one because it does a fantastic job. Does is have the bells and whistles of an iRobot. Nope, but I don't need room barriers or anything fancy and the price is spot on for what is does. All of my floors are a mix of tile and hardwood with only a couple of low pile rugs at doors, maybe that matters for battery life. My particular unit will run for 3-4 hours on a charge and is a very thorough little machine. Can it clean where it can't fit, of course not, but it does an excellent job for what it is and my floors have never been cleaner. Mine does get hung up on the transition trim between the tile and hardwood sometimes, but it is not the machines fault it gets caught on the trim and when it squawks for help, I move it and push the button. No biggie. My expectations for this machine are met, and having a little common sense says 'Is it perfect?' of course not, but I read the description before purchasing and knew exactly what I was and was not getting. Am I happy with my purchase, absolutely. Would I buy one again. Yes.

R549:	I don't know why everyone is so enamored with this thing. I have had it over a year and I constantly have to baby sit it. It constantly gets stuck under chairs or shelving units, sometimes even corners. I find it sitting there beeping or dead if I leave it alone too long. I have to pick move throw rugs otherwise it will get stuck on them. The scheduled feature has never worked properly. Eufy says because my floors are too dark. Three apartments in a year, and didn't work properly on a single one of them. Even tried to program it on white counter tops and that didn't work. But seriously... who doesn't have dark colored floors? Not that I actually want it to work because I would come home to find it stuck somewhere anyway. I will give it credit for one thing. It's durable. As I'm cooking or at my standing desk and it's running over my toes repeatedly, I give it a good kick and it keeps on going... only to bang into some other piece of furniture the sensors didn't pick up. And it will pick up a good amount of stuff, but the brushes do tend to "bat" larger items. Oh, and be careful, it will go over stairs... got out onto the balcony once and I barely saved it from falling 14 stories below once. Explain that to the police department. As for eufy... I reached out to them about advanced trouble shooting regarding the scheduling, clearly stating the steps I already tried as suggested on the Amazon product page. The proceeded to tell me to try the same steps, but there's nothing they can go, it's out of warranty by about a month. Guess I should have been more worried about dealing with trivial things instead of dealing with hurricane aftermath and moving twice since. I debated how many stars to give... Two felt a little low cause it does ultimately do what it's supposed to and I don't have to do it myself... But the advertised features that don't quite live up and the fact I have to baby sit it and still need to spot clean after it runs makes three feel high. Ultimately, I guess I don't like it and wish I would have used the warranty and tried a different one.

R552:	Pros: Super handy. Don’t know how I lived for so long without one of these. I vacuum more frequently now since it doesn’t take any time off my day and I don’t have to go through the trouble of digging for the full sized vacuum in the closet. I just keep this one out, discreetly under a side table and turn it on with the remote whenever I want. I love that it has a remote and it's pretty simple to operate, as I'm not into connecting gadgets to my phone. Super practical and despite its small sized dust reservoir, it does a good job in keeping my hardwood floor clean and it also does corners pretty well with the little brush arms, which is great. It has two filters and the plastic one is easily removable and washable, as is the dust box compartment. Super practical. Cons: It doesn’t vacuum near its base, which is kind of annoying. It always keeps a distance from it, even if you try to send it there with the remote, it keeps turning around and going the other way. You either have to unplug the base and then send eufy there with the remote, which is kind of a pain, make peace with having that area more dusty than the rest of the house, or use a full sized regular vacuum in that area. Also, it doesn't seem to hold a charge as well as when I first got it. The sensors sometimes work great in keeping eufy from bumping into furniture, but for some reason, at other times, don’t seem to work at all, in that the eufy will go straight into a collision course with an object or piece or furniture, and bangs right into it, head on. All said, I’m happy with it overall. It’s practical and keeps the floor clean. However, the most annoying thing about eufy, besides not vacuuming near its base, is that it sometimes refuses to go under certain pieces of furniture where there’s definitely room for it to go under. Both my coffee table and my tv stand have about an inch of room above eufy, but it often refuses to go under them, even though there’s no obstruction on the floor. And what’s funny is that at other times it does goes under those pieces with no problem and takes its time there. So I don’t get it. On the days when eufy isn’t feeling like going under the furniture, I try to send it there with the remote, but it still refuses. It keeps turning the other way when it gets too close to the coffee table or tv stand. That’s the major annoyance. Aside from that, I’m loving not having to vacuum anymore.

R554:	Is 3 years long enough? Worked fine for 3 years and now it just starts up and the light goes red and it stops and beeps for 30 seconds and turns off. Yes, it's been charged. Battery died? Something. I don't know why I waited so long to buy one of these things. I was a little leery of the unknown name brand but once the product came, I was impressed with the quality. I'm doubly impressed with how well it works. I did not expect it to pick up as much as it did the first time I used it. Frankly, I was kind of shocked at how much I was (obviously) missing by using a regular upright. Plus, this thing is just fun. It's like having a tiny semi-dumb robot wandering around your house that happens to be doing an excellent job of picking up the dirt you usually miss and often don't even see. It's not going to pick up paper or big things (come on.. you're not that much of a slob are you?), but for what it was designed for? Great product, well priced, high quality and downright fun to have around. It will get hung up from time to time. If you leave out a particularly thick rug or have a lot of wires on the floor that isn't tucked away, it can get stuck. It also tries to climb things (like my bathroom scale) from time to time, vs. navigating around it, and get's stuck, but rarely. When it does, it kinda cry's by beeping for a few minutes. Then it shuts down and waits for you to find it. All you have to do is hit the button on top and it starts right up again. Mine runs for almost 2 hours before the battery runs down and it, every so slowly, wanders back to its charging station, positions itself to recharge, and shuts off. I'm still amazed every time I start it up before leaving and coming home later in the day with a house that's been vacuumed and a little robot safely back in it's charger. It's kinda magical in a way. Kinda.

R555:	The eufy did a great job cleaning up most of the debris in my kitchen and mudroom areas, both of which are tiled. It seemed overly invested in cleaning the cat tree in said area, but I digress (it took the finish off the edges, because it would spend about 30 minutes of battery life going around in a 6 square inch square). It functioned well, and when I would rinse off the brushes, from time to time, the plastic fibers would "remember" their shape. I had to clean out bits of fur (pets) and my hair from the wheels and brushes, but that just proved it was sucking up trash. With no notice, it completely died about 3 days after the one year warranty lapsed. Those engineers who design these things to fail are clearly doing a great job. Unfortunately for me, the battery seems totally dead: it won't keep a charge. So, buy this and know that you run the risk of repeating what happened to me, and that's a dead battery/device.

R556:	Listen, I was probably like you. You probably heard your relatives or friends telling you "it's rubbish, don't buy it. It'll get stuck everywhere." Then you see the massive amount of reviews on Amazon and think "it'll probably be fine, they're just exaggerating." They weren't. This robot, while quiet, effective at picking up even the finest sand (PLAY sand, even!), and attractive, simply got stuck more often than not, and spent a lot of time recleaning areas it had already went over. Essentially, no matter how well it cleans, it's useless if it bumps around in the same area until the battery dies. I strongly recommend to the manufacturer that they look into intelligent pathing, and that you, the consumer, either wait for them to do so, or buy a unit that has intelligent pathing. Additionally, the robot doesn't always self return, and has died right in front of the charging station. $220 is too much to ask for such ineffective pathing.

R557:	I loved this when I got it. About 8 months in, the roller stopped and they replaced it with a new unit. Told me the new unit would have the same 1 year warranty. Received that and i was pleased again. Then, 8 months into that the battery is always dead. Now Eufy says they only warrant their replacement (brand new unit btw) for only 3 months. So for $250 I got 16 months of vacuuming. Also, this is great on rugs, fits under furniture well, but is not good on hardwood floors with the pet hair. Dust yes, hair no. If you get this, purchase extended warranty because you will need it. Very disappointed in the service. If you have a new product, it should have the 1 year warranty ESPECIALLY if it is replacing a new unit that crapped out after 8 months. In essence, I only got 11 months of warranty. Shame on your service. It is very telling when they only warrant a NEW replacement for 3 months. Bad Eufy!

R558:	We've had this little fella in our home for about 11 months now. My little dog barely notices any more. Great job with a mundane task. However... There are "intelligence" or programming issues with this machine. Firstly, if it ever gets hung up somewhere, i.e. on a thick rug, under a cabinet, under the kitchen table, under a bed/couch/chair, it will always get hung up in the same spots. You have to make a change to prevent it from going to those places. OK, I can do that. But now, nearly a year later, one of the drive wheels is failing. He won't go in a straight line any more. You can hear clicks like plastic gears are stripping. Not good. Our little vac really did a great job, but longevity needs improved. 200-300 per year for a vacuum is a bit too much too swallow. Intelligence also needs improved. Their needs to be several, pre-programmed avoidance or evasion plans built into the system. Because the one, which is pretty good, does not work all of the time. In fact it fails all of the time in the same exact places. Now, it will not work at all because it will not move correctly. Smart money may want to look at other offerings. Update: 8-23-18 Tried again to call customer service. They didn't open until 9am PST. I'm in CST... so had to wait till after work. Called them @ 4:35 CST got a recording that all customer service personnel were in a meeting to learn how to better serve their customers! For starters, leave personnel in place to answer customer calls... WOW! Still trying to get warranty repair before it expires. UPDATE: I got an email from customer support following this review. They have sent me a replacement RoboVac. We'll see if this one holds up better. Fingers crossed!

R559:	Purchased this vacuum in June 2017 based on numerous positive reviews and "best of" articles. It operated great for the first three months. It was cleaning a small area which included my kitchen, dining area, and living room. After about 3 months it started randomly shutting off during it's cleaning cycle. As time went on this got worse to the point where the vacuum would turn off every minute or two. I followed some online help and customer service suggestions to fix the issues; however nothing would help. I received a replacement around October 2017. Unfortunately the replacement had the same issues. Based on the numerous positive reviews, my situation could be a fluke. However, I requested a full refund, which Eufy provided. Eufy customer service was top notch and I give them a 5/5. Unfortunately I can't say the same for this vacuum.

R560:	I love this vacuum in theory. When it is working properly I love it in reality. But I have not had one that has lasted over three months yet. Thankfully there is an 18-month warranty and the company has continually replaced these. They are very fast and pretty much just take your word for it. I have even offered to return them and they have declined. Both of my eufys have just quit working. They spin in circles until they begin beeping to let you know. According to the company it seems to be some sort of sensor chip malfunction. Would not buy one of these again but if they ever improve their design I might be open to it because when they are operating properly they are fantastic. I have three dogs and a cat that lives inside as well as a 4-year old child . Aside from the malfunction they're excellent to pick up pet hair dander and even larger items. They are quite simple to maintain and take apart to clean. I think this company is on to something but they have some improving to do. I have been running my eufy since September of 2017 and am on my third eufy.
	S1:	I love this vacuum in theory.
	PosTag:	[PRP, VBP, DT, NN, IN, NN, .]

R562:	The good: It vacuums way better than my Roomba ever did - I cannot stress that enough. It was almost embarrassing how much dirt this little thing found on what were freshly cleaned floors. It was so good at its job that we had no choice but to replace the maid since she clearly wasn't doing her best. Run time is great - about an hour and a half on a full charge - just park the thing overnight and you're good to go in the morning. We loved it for all of five days. The bad: It lasted five days. We found it doing jerky back and forth, side to side movements while mournfully beeping that its front bumper was stuck. After removing the bumper - no big deal, just a few tiny screws - no obstruction was found. A call to customer service confirmed a bad sensor. An RMA was issued and replacement was promised but has not been seen in over a week; no replacement shipment notification either. Based upon reps tone and other reviews, bad sensors seems to be the "thing" with this unit. So, we really did want to love this thing but it is going back while Amazon is still willing to take it back - waiting over a week for a replacement unit shipment notification is just too long. Too bad...

R564:	I'd give it six stars if I could! I did a ton of research trying to find a robot that would pick up pet hair, lots of it. We have 4 dogs, all indoor and it's like a hair farm around here. I would highly recommend to anyone with tile floors and lots of dust and dander on a daily basis. This little guy spends about 1-1 1/2 hours combing the floor, under tables, around table and chair legs, hallways, bathroom etc just quietly gathering the bits and pieces of "stuff". (Note: pick up dog toys, cords, anything it could get caught up on before you launch it). This is my new favorite cleaning device (I don't have many but I only buy what is proven to work). Eufy RoboVac exceeded my expectations and the price point is perfect. I am hoping the company comes out with a battery that I can buy when this one runs down. Other reviews have noted that it is in the works. Hoping they deliver, otherwise, that could be a deal breaker. But I remain hopeful and terribly happy with this workhorse. UPDATE May 2019: Robot quit working and started a series of 4 beeps. Cleaned it thoroughly as well as charger, tried to charge it directly, tried to find a way to reset it. Nada. Called customer service and yes, the one year warranty was up. They said "well, you can order a replacement battery off of Amazon and see if that solves the problem, if it doesnʻt you can return the battery". If you look at battery replacements on Amazon, the one for this robot does not work. AND, they donʻt accept battery returns. She then offered me a deal on buying a new one. MMMM...sorry. Iʻm done with you Eufy, weʻre breaking up for good. You have a great product...until it stops working. Planned obsolescence.

R569:	Here is some context so you know how I used the Eufy. I have ALL hard floor surfaces....approximately 1000 sq. ft. When I would run the Eufy, I would take up all my rugs, so the Eufy only went on hard surfaces in my home. I would run it once a week, but sometimes once every 10-14 days. Never more often than that. I have 2 short-haired dogs that shed very little. Each time I'd run Eufy, I'd have to empty it. It worked REALLY great....until it didn't. I kept the brushes clean and maintained the Eufy per the instructions, which was really simple and not time consuming. Point is, I took really good care of it and didn't run the thing every single day. I was so excited about this product when I found it! It worked perfect for approximately 9 months. There is a warranty of 1 year. After about 6 months, the robotics stopped working. When I would start it, it would undock and act as if it were going to clean. But, it would just spin in circles and then stop with an error (red blinking light). I contacted the manufacturer. They were really easy to work with. We troubleshot the problem for about 20 minutes and it didn't resolve the problem. She concluded that she needed to process a warranty exchange and sent me a new Eufy. I was pleased. I figured I just got a lemon. The new unit worked great for about 11 months. Then, the same thing happened. Now it's out of warranty and my only option is to buy another unit. For a couple hundred bucks, I expect the unit to last more than 6 months. I'm disappointed because I thought I found a great product that compared to the "big name" and more expensive robot vacuums. So, the moral of the story. I guess you get what you pay for?? I was told by Eufy that they have improved the robotics, which I don't doubt. But, I still don't want to spend another $250+ for something that won't last more than 6-9 months.

R570:	Pros: Inexpensive, good suction, gets under couches, excellent customer service Cons: Object Avoidance Mode stops functioning, black rugs can be problematic UPDATED 7/16/2017: Eufy sent me another unit to try out before sending back the first two. This one was used (there was still dirt in the tray), but it worked great—for about two days. Then its Object Avoidance failed just like the first two. There is either something systemically wrong with the chipset on the RoboVac 11 models or I have an unusual amount of bad luck. Eufy's email customer service was very prompt and courteous and allowed me to ship back all three units with no charge for shipping. And along with the full refund, they sent me a free Anker product for my trouble (I chose a portable charger). I'm hoping the next model RoboVac will have this problem fixed. If nothing else, this experience has convinced me to get another robot vacuum cleaner; my floors have never been cleaner. I just won't be getting another RoboVac 11. I'm keeping the rating at 3 stars mostly for the great customer service. But keep an eye on your RoboVac and watch out for the bumping-into-objects problem, especially if it's still under warranty. UPDATED 6/25/2017: Now Robbie's Object Avoidance stops working in about 14 seconds. Whatever is going on with these 2 units, it gets worse over time. I'm corresponding with Eufy and may just get a refund. These were on sale, so I bought two of them. (My home has two levels.) I have owned these units for about a month now. I named one “Rosie,” and the other one “Robbie,” for obvious sci-fi reasons. (These are house-cleaning robots, after all!) And it's obvious I'm also not the first to do this. I was initially very impressed with these vacuums. I had expected a glorified rug sweeper but they actually have some decent suction. While following along behind them, I can actually feel a decent amount of air blowing out from behind them. I ran both for the first time without vacuuming the house myself, and both ran until the battery ran low. Trays on both were VERY full. Run time is about 2 hours for each of them, slightly better than the 1.5 hours they promise. And they were very quiet, but now they bump into things which can get loud. Object Avoidance Mode (OAM) has stopped working correctly. OAM works at first, but within a few seconds on Rosie, and within a few minutes on Robbie, cleaning becomes a series of seemingly random collisions, sometimes hard, with walls and furniture. At first, I thought this was a sensor issue but now I think it’s a software issue. They both find their charging bases just fine. I have cleaned the front on both units where the sensors are located but the problem persists. I was going to send Rosie back, but Robbie has started having the same issue; it just takes him longer to start acting up. I first noticed this today. They both still manage to get the floors clean in my 1,800 sq.ft. house. I think I’ll go ahead and keep both of them, and hope that the 1-year warranty will be honored if they get worse. Considering that I bought both of these on sale for less than the cost of a single low-end Roomba and that they can get under my couches and chairs where the Roomba can’t, I’ll consider these worth keeping. You will need to robot-proof your house. Gather up all of your electrical cords. If you have black rugs, this vacuum may or may not have an issue with it. I think it depends on the material the rug is made of. Both of my units have no problem with my black bathroom rugs, but will consistently “get stuck” on the black areas of my multi-colored floor rugs in my living room and den. I had to get creative in keeping them out of those areas. On your small light-weight rugs, you may need to get some rug grippers or double-sided tape. They can suck up a rug corner and get stuck.

I basically have a huge expensive hockey puck on my living room floor that serves no purpose. Update: I added a star to my review as Eufy customer service reached out to me after seeing my initial review. They offered and did send me a refurbished replacement for my non-working vac. At the time of this review the replacement is working and it is my hope that it continues to work. While I am skeptical of the vac I can say that Eufy's customer support is outstanding. My original vac was outside the warranty time period and technically they were under no obligation to do anything to correct my situation. The fact that they contacted me to try and make it right speaks volumes about this company. If I could give a rating separately for their service I would give them 5 stars for their customer service. I have not had the replacement vac long enough to change my initial opinion of it at this time.

R572:	The Eufy RoboVac 11 is a great little vacuum that does a great job for the price. The downside is as they always say "You get what you pay for". The vacuum lasts about 8-10 months and even with regular care and maintenance it will still go out on you. Luckily Eufy has a great warranty program but the downside is the warranty is not extended or renewed when it is replaced and your only option at that point is to buy a new one at full price. While I love the price of the Eufy I'll spend it else where to get a product that will last a bit long. Pros: Price Warranty Service - This is quick and only takes about 7-14 days to process you a replacement for the faulty unit. Quick free Amazon Shipping Cons: Battery Life - This thing starts to degrade quickly and it is not a user replaceable part. Cleaning Pattern - The vacuum will just wonder around aimlessly for 2 hours until the battery gets low. Then it wonders around looking for the dock. Longevity - I wouldn't expect this to last longer than the first year. Maintenance Cost - Getting official replacement parts is expensive and honestly isn't worth the hassle since it doesn't make a difference to change the spin brushes every 3 months, filter every 2, and beater bar every 6.

R576:	Works great as far as suction, but it's not a very smart vacuum. It goes around in no particular order bumping into things and usually misses big areas of the house before it runs out of battery. It does have a good battery life, so it can usually do a good job chalked up to perseverance. Because it doesn't have an intelligent way of navigating, it just goes forward until it bumps into something and then moves in a different direction. Sometimes this means that it just gets stuck in the same area of a room cleaning in a circle. It also almost never finds it's dock to re-charge when it's done (maybe 20% of the time?). I don't run it when I'm not home because it will usually get stuck on things and I have to go rescue it. I will say that it's a huge improvement on vacuuming or sweeping on my own, and I don't regret buying it- it's just that for the price I would think the technology would be much better.

R588:	I bought this back in 2017 and I left an early, semi neutral review. Well I'm back in 2019 to say dont buy this or any Eufy vacuum. The 11 has to be the dumbest piece of electronics I've ever bought in my life, and I buy a lot of electronics. Where do I start....can barely navigate dark carpet. Cant manage itself over floor vents. It FORCES itself to get wedged into anything possible....between couches, under a chair that it should know to bounce off of but instead keeps ramming itself into...it gets stuck on the edge of stairs. It will randomly start driving in a circle then throw an error. It will throw an error just cleaning. The rubber on one of the wheels not randomly comes off. I can go on and on about how dumb this thing is. I recently bought a Deebot which I returned 2 hours later because it too was dumber than a box of rocks (it would constantly just plow into its dock when trying to return and it also experiences similar errors). I will never buy a Eufy product again. Maybe I'm just the unluckiest guy when it comes to vacuums.

R589:	I really like this robot vacuum....when it works. We ordered one on Sept 4th, 2017. We have vinyl floors or ceramic through out the house. So no carpet. It did a wonderful job of keeping the floors tidy and picking up the pet hair. We have no small children in the house, we are empty nesters. After a month of scheduled daily operation, it quit working. It just one day stopped and would only spin in a circle. Being a IT guy, I tried rebooting it...no change. Removed the battery, waited several minutes with the power switch on, then replaced the battery. No change. I frankly forgot about it sitting in its dock for a month before I contacted Eufy Support via email (support@eufylife.com). This experience was not as bad as I was expecting. The asked me to charge it directly with the power supply, clean the contacts and senor array with a clean cloth. When that did not work, they asked me to send them video of the issue. Responses were prompt and their troubleshooting steps were complete. After the video they sent me another unit. My wife was very happy. Happy wife, Happy life! 2 weeks of again normal scheduled operation, this unit starts doing the exact same thing. This time it appears it has lost forward drive as I have been unable to get it to move forward, even manually controlling it with the remote. I have contacted Eufy Support again by reopening the same ticket. We will see what results this produces. Like I said, I enjoy Eufy when it works. I am willing to give them the chance to fix this before I ask for a refund.

It started getting errors and I was able to get it going again for awhile. We changed filters and brushes fairly regularly. It would work for awhile and then give false errors. R591:	A must have if you have pets. You will be shocked how much hair/dust it picks up every single day. Cannot testify how good it is on carpet... I have only used it once in a carpeted area, and it seemed to do an OK job. Definitely good enough for daily use then deep clean with a more powerful vacuum biweekly. UPDATE 1/2/2020 Changed from 5 starts to 2. The first one crapped out within 2 months, Eufy was quick to send me a new one. That one lasted for a year with some weird bugs (sometimes would just stop and flash red) ... after a year (past the warranty) it started to not be functional. It just beeps constantly - I have looked up troubleshooting tips and nothing seems to work. I even replaced the brush roll. Im giving a 2 star instead of 1 because at least euphy has been responsive in trying to help. But I really am of the mindset that a purchase like this should last at least 4 years. And it barely lasted 1 year (with the first one lasting 2 months). Quality is a big deal to me as I strive to reduce waste.

R601:	OK, THIS will be the final edit. I've given up on it. Back to 2 stars. There is some flaw in the infra-red sensor(s) whereby they fail after a few days use so the vacuum bangs into things. This will and has scarred up walls, furniture, etc... The wipe off the front trick worked for awhile but is now of no effect. It's too bad, I wanted to like this and very much did when it worked properly. Customer service sent a free one to replace the first defective one so they did their best. Final edit and a USAGE TIP - Once again, customer service is not great from a process standpoint but they have actually solved the problem in an expeditious and generous way. TIP - If the vacuum loses it's avoidance ability and starts running into things, wipe off the front of the curved bumper with a cloth. I know it looks clean. I know it will look approximately the same after you wipe it. I know this sounds dumb. But try it. This restores the avoidance behavior on mine. Maybe it's magic; like a lamp. Edited AGAIN - I was too harsh on customer service. After I returned the vac to Amazon I was contacted again and Eufy has bent over backward to make things right. We'll see how the vacuum works out but the customer service has gone above and beyond. (Yes, if I could think of another cliche I'd probably use it, too.) Edited - from 5 stars to 2 Since the original review, this has become a disappointment. I can forgive the occasional missed run-time and it getting stuck under things but its ability to avoid objects in front of it has gone away so it bangs into furniture, walls, etc.... Eventually everything will be scarred up so it's going back. Customer service is not problem solving oriented, sending form responses suggesting cleaning the bumpers (duh, it runs into things so the bumpers work, the problem is in the infrared sensors) and asking for videos in response to an inquiry that complains that it runs into things. If you look at the manufacturer's comments to poor reviews, you'll see the form of response you'll get. A waste of time. Original- I've had previous generation Roombas and Neatos. This is better - and cheaper. It is well thought out and its inputs are simple and logical. It runs a long time on one charge, more than an hour and a half, and as long as it's not in a separate room returns to its charging station when finished. It can be programmed (easily) to start automatically at the same time each day. The vac does not run into large items (walls, sofas, corners, etc) but it will impact smaller obstructions such as chair legs, shoes and similar. It doesn't travel at a high rate of speed so even those are fairly gentle impacts. Suction is fine, leading to dumping the bin about every cycle. Cleaning the dust bin is easy and not messy. I thought having a remote was just a gimmick but it, too, is well designed and convenient to use. All and all, I am pleasantly surprised at its excellent engineering and performance. Considering the price of the more well known competitors, it's a bargain.

R604:	Edit(11/13/18): I’m afraid I’ve come to the end of road with Eufy. The machine worked fine, most of the time, but it just didn’t last. It doesn’t make sense to pay that much for something that will last only 6 months. Since my original machine was out of warranty, they don’t care if the second one malfunctioned as well. I gave an additional star for customer service and honoring the first warranty, but I can’t buy it again and I recommend you don’t either. Edit (11/11/18): I’m unhappy again. In less than 6 months, BRAND NEW “upgraded” unit did the same thing! It alarms saying the brush is stuck. There was nothing wrapped around the brush or any visible reason for it to be stuck. I even replaced the brush, but it still alarmed and does not work at this point. I’ll try customer service again. Edit (5/10/18): I’m happy again! Their upgraded replacement Eufy arrived in 2 days on a Sunday morning - super fast. This new unit has been cleaning very well. I had trouble getting the schedule to run properly, even after getting the appropriate beeps after programming, but it finally stuck. Customer service is definitely superb! I hope this one continues working as well as it is now. Edit (4/27/18): Since several other reviews mentioned customer service, I contacted them after the last review. After a few exchanges of videos and troubleshooting attempts, they concluded it was a faulty unit and are shipping another. I’ll update how that goes. Edit (4/17/18): Now 6 months in and the stars are falling Down from a 5 to 3 and possibly more. :(. Occasionally, Eufy would “forget” the schedule for no known reason. Even after explicitly setting it to the same thing, it woudn’t go. Eventually, it would catch and all would be well again. It’s been much worse in the last month. What makes it even worse - to the point I’m ready to ditch it - it that it won’t go for more than two minutes without alarming — for NO reason! It’s running over a perfectly smooth, clear, hardwood floor and just stops and alarms. SO disappointing! Oh, Eufy, I so want to like you again! It's still early (just 4 days in), but I love my Eufy so far! While not perfect, it gets up a significant amount of dust and dog hair from our hardwood floors every day. Every little bit helps! I'm still learning its idiosyncrasies.
