R605:	My unit went wrong just out of warranty. I took it apart and found that despite being a vacuum cleaner, the main motor is not well sealed. It was jammed full of hair. I contacted Eufy for repair, but they don’t repair. I asked where I can buy a new motor, but they don’t sell parts either. They did offer me a discount on a new unit, which is better than nothing I suppose. If you’re comfortable spending over $200 on a year’s worth of robot vacuuming then fine, the unit works reasonably well. Otherwise buy a brand with better quality.

R607:	I had an iRobot that worked great until the battery died. I got this one based on great reviews and the relatively low cost compared to iRobot. This turned out not to be a smart purchase. Often, the robot will beep, asking to be rescued due to one reason or another. If you don't react fast enough, it turns into where is my robot hunting game. When it is not stuck somewhere, it will likely ran out of juice before it tried to return to the home base to charge. On a few occasions, the robot will get so very close to the home base, but will fail to dock itself correctly to start charging. I am guessing either there is a fundamental design flaw in power monitoring / management or I am unlucky to get a defective unit. Overall, the robot requires too much baby sitting, we simply don't use it anymore. Another white elephant in the house.

R610:	Straight off, I really liked the Eufy. It kept the floor tidy, and let us save the bigger vacuum for more thorough cleanings. It cleaned and made it back home successfully maybe 75% of the time. It got stuck in maybe three places consistently: one over dark floor vents, and a couple of places where it wedged itself under a cabinet. Then suddenly it stopped working. Beeping during charging. Contacted Eufy support. They said 15 months old, so no longer under warranty. Nothing they would do. From hints on the internet and personal experience, I suspect that either the battery no longer charges, or something in the charging mechanism itself is borked. You can replace rollers and such, but not the battery. For something I expected to work for several years, I'm pretty disappointed. That makes it a pricy, disposable toy. I'm considering a new vac, but certainly a different brand that I think will last longer.

I mean, don't we all, but scales seem to be about the only things he'll aggressively push around. I do have a couple of small rugs in my bathroom. He'll wander around for an hour and not get everywhere. 2) He doesn't obey when I tell him to go back to his dock. I'll push the home button on the remote and he'll sing at me to let me know he understood, then he'll go back to wandering around randomly. I push it a couple more times and the same thing happens. Eventually, I end up using the remote to guide him close, and then he figures it out.

R652:	His name is Hungry Boy and he's an idiot and I love him. I run this weekly to keep my 100% tile apartment floors from getting gross on my feet. He runs into black stuff and tries to vacuum over bars of my folding tables, god bless him. He got stuck on the anti-fatigue mat in the kitchen when he tries to dismount it at an angle, and it's not that steep. He literally can't find his dock if he's more than two feet from it. He largely just does the same area over and over again if you don't move him yourself if you're in a small apartment with a little hall like me. He will literally vacuum over my feet which TICKLES SO MUCH. But Eufy/Anker are very ON TOP OF IT and sent a kind e-mail with instructions to fix my schedule problem and some running tips. Most of these little issues don't mean much in the long run, unless you have really particular robo vacuum needs. You should maybe check out a higher price range or the newer IQ boost models. I still use him often and still adore him. And I can tell if I forgot to run him before, because the bulk of the tile is always noticeably smooth. But for the price range, he's a GREAT robot vacuum. Really good suction and perfect for tile floors. It takes a few passes on low pile carpets like small, thin rugs. But he does do that on his own. With the tile it's great. No more hair, no more kitty litter, no more dirt and dust, no more crumbs. Hungry boy has GOT THIS. He gets right up against the baseboards and underneath tables, desks, and shoe racks. His tank is big enough for two runs of my apartment. The filter works very well at cutting allergens. You can hear him running from another room, but he's not loud at all or even annoying. He's not a smart vacuum. He's got no apps and won't learn. He's just a dumb little hungry robot who will help you with your floors, so don't be expecting a thousand dollar from this little guy. But DO expect to make your life so much easier. With my disabilities, he is a lifesaver. I don't even own a broom anymore. My Husband likes to put him in manual mode and clean the floors FOR FUN!!!! HE DOES CHORES FOR FUN!!! He's a hit with guests. My cat isn't a big fan of him but Hungry boy can't see black things so that's Hungry boy's fault. I was hoping they'd team up and fight crime in my community. She smugly tolerates him from heights instead, like batman. The bottom line is that this little robo does a lot of the vacuuming for you as long as you clear all cables and cords (he has dragged my cat's fountain out of the wall) and thick rugs from his path. His suction is also pretty serious, he will suck the heck out of bathroom rugs that are thin enough to let him ride. There are suction marks and my rug is always dragged around the bathroom. ---- EDIT: 6/20/18 purchased 4/22/17 It's been a year and his battery doesn't seem to be as strong as it used to be. Instead of dying somewhere near the dock (or even making it back to the dock, he did do that maybe 3/5ths of the time) I usually find him tuckered out in the living room now. I was sort of anticipating a longer battery life from this company since that their parent company makes some fantastic rechargeable portable batteries. I ended up having to buy a broom. I hope there's a firmware upgrade or something to help optimize his runtime so I can get more out of the reduced battery life. At the rate it's degrading I'll probably need another hungry boy within 2 years so I hope the battery life stops fading. tl;dr: Pros: great for tile, massive effort saver, runs pretty quiet. Cons: you need to babysit him or do some serious floor prep to keep him away from danger or getting stuck

R670:	The saga of our Vacuum "Brenda Bot" continues with a thud. We have cleaned the unit and tried to restart but she continues to run in to the walls blindly. It appears a sensor has gone bad. It is still able to clean just bounces from wall to wall at full speed. I reached out to customer service this morning and will wait to hear back. My original review is below and still works the same. I spoke with their customer service and they were determined to make it right. I still have a use for the unit although not the area I had planned. Again I think the product is good just not for every home. This is my first robo vacuum and was pretty excited to try it out. At first I wasn't disappointed. It has good suction, travels over all our floor mats without issue, and is very quiet. The main issue with this unit is that it gets stuck every time it cleans. I think the front bumper could be designed in such a way that doesn't allow it to wedge under things. It got stuck both under the fridge door and a decorative table. The only options to stop it from getting stuck is to block in to rooms it doesn't have issues or alter our house. Our floor plan is very open so there is not a practical way to box it in to a room. One feature that would fix this is virtual walls which this vacuum doesn't support. All of that said it is still a great product for the price if your expectations are realistic and your rooms don't have furniture the exact wedging height. As a bonus it keeps the kids entertained for an hour while they chase it around. It even survived my youngest trying to ride it. If you have young kids this will probably happen and they will also see how much it can "eat". Always check the dust bin when emptying for "keep" items.

R672:	I've been using this for about a week now. My 3-star rating is based solely on how it works for me. This is my first robotic vacuum, so bear in mind that I have nothing to compare it to other than my upright, a Eureka "Multicyclonic" (has a designation for "Pet"). We have two dogs and two cats. So, yeah. The Eureka does an amazing job with pet fur on every surface, high pile carpet, low pile carpet, tile, hardwood floors. There are two knocks on the Eureka: 1) Can't do stairs and, 2) can't get under the beds. The RoboVac can't do stairs either, but it can get under beds. With our zoo, we really should vacuum daily, or at least every other day. But we're busy folks, and the last thing we want to do when we get home is vacuum. Hence, the impetus to try the RoboVac. First negative was the instruction on the amount of space required for the charging base: Two meters straight out and one meter on both sides, where there is an outlet nearby. This is probably overkill. When I started the RoboVac, it pulled straight out, and when I sent it "home", it positioned itself about two meters directly in front, and then turned and went into slow crawl back to the base. If I were keeping this (more below), I'd experiment with the space requirements. BTW, several reviews have mentioned how quiet the RoboVac is, and I give it five stars on that. Before the first use, I gave our floors a thorough cleaning with the upright. The following day, I put the RoboVac through its paces. I did not pick up or move anything because I wanted to get a real world test of what it could do and how it would avoid obstacles. I was impressed with its ability to avoid rag towels that we use to wipe the dogs' feet when they come in from the outside during the wet, soggy season here in Michigan. Same with dog toys. It handled the transition from tile floor to a room rug with no problem. It really does appear to move in a very random pattern, and I'm pretty sure that it hopes to cover the entire surface in the time a full battery charge gives it. I did notice where it covered the same area several times before it finally "found" an area it hadn't yet touched. That behavior doesn't give me confidence that it will always cover the entire area each time it runs. The RoboVac moved with ease on all of our surfaces. So, now, to the thing that really counts, its ability to clean. It did a pretty good job on the hardwood and tile floors, and it is almost worth keeping on its ability to clean the hardwood floors under our four beds, but not quite. The cleaning performance on the carpet and rugs was poor, and I had to use our upright to finish the job. Mind you that I had the "Max" setting on. Also, the roller brush required a lot of cleaning to pull the pet fur out (every day), which is a nasty job. (Somehow, our Eureka only needs the roller brush cleaned out once per month.) So, for those reasons, I will be returning the RoboVac. Obviously, YMMV. For homes without four furry critters, the RoboVac may perform very well.
	S1:	I've been using this for about a week now.

R675:	This seems good so far after a month of usage. It replaces routine Swiffering for my 2700 sq ft house. I have mostly tile and wood floors. It gets caught on any clothes on the floor, as well as some wires. Other wires it powers over them. There is no way to instruct it to avoid certain areas, but I knew that when I bought it and the limitation is reflected in the price. For example, it always gets stuck if it tries to go behind my computer desk, which is annoying. If you are looking for a cheap robot vacuum, then this one is good. It got good reviews when I looked around. The higher end vacuums are too expensive considering their use-case, which is replacing a Swiffer. Update: after using it for a longer period of time it is frustrating how frequently I have to rescue it. It gets stuck on something nearly every run. Sometimes it runs out of batteries and stops. It would be better if it started heading back to the dock when the batteries get low.

R684:	My second robotic vaccum. My first was a Neato about the same price ($10 difference). Positives (compared to the Neato): - Sound: compared to Neato, the Robovac is very quite. - lower profile: fit under more furniture - this one came with the side brushes compared to the Neato I had at that price point, Neato didn't have it. Negatives (Compared to Neato): - Can't set cleaning schedules: I can set a time for the vac to operate, but it will be on everyday which is pointless. - sucking power: a small caveat, but Neato was stronger (and more noisy). I don't have pets so I don't know how important that is. The Robovac was "adequate". - Big one (why this is going back): this is a dumb Robovac. It randomly moves around the room with no apparent plan or strategy until it pumps something and changes directions! Going back to its base for recharging is a messy and long ordeal. I one time tested it by asking it to go back to charging base literally right after it left the base, what should have been an L shap 5 second trip took the vac around the dining room and kitchen for over 25 min!!! I have never tried the Roomba but this one is not ready yet. I guess for one open space room (a basement with no sections to it) it might be ok.

R692:	Bought this to replace a 2nd generation Roomba that finally died. We use this in our finished basement. Cleans really well. We have one large rug and a Rottweiler. Cleans all hair in a single pass. My problem is the unit got "trapped" under our end table. I've attached a short video. The unit entered about 20 minutes into the cleaning cycle and couldn't get out. It eventually ran out of battery. I bought this unit to run automatically at night. This issue is a fatal flaw in my opinion. I'll need to look to see if there is an option to update software. UPDATE 12/2017 - I've had this unit for months. I have it set up in auto mode (start at same time every day). In the last few months there hasn't been one time this unit didn't get wedged/stuck trying to go under a piece of furniture where it clearly wouldn't fit. Added photos. Heard back from customer service: "he RoboVac detects with infrared ray and objects with very dark surface absorb the ray so the RoboVac will not be able to recognize them and will move forward and bump into the furniture and gets stuck." Based on this feedback I would not recommend getting this robot if you have dark furniture with a clearance gap under it. The vacuum initially bumps into the furniture, then lowers itself, then proceeds to get stuck under the edge. This occurs nearly every time the vacuum runs. I have it set up to run at a specific time each day. Once in about 2 weeks I'll find that it made it back to the charger successfully; all other days it's either stuck under the table behind my couch or our bar.

R698:	It's only been 2 days, but here is some initial feedback.... The product came quickly and in great shape. I charged it like the instructions listed and after it was ready, it went off to clean my floors. It doesn't really follow any pattern and does a little cleaning here and then there, but eventually it comes back and cleans pretty well. It has a very hard time on carpet and thank goodness we have tile and hardwood on most of the bottem floor, but I would NOT recommend this product for heavy carpet cleaning. The other thing that is a bit frustrating is it cannot find its way back home. I even pushed the button on the remote to go home....and after 45 minutes of going everywhere but home, I used the remote to direct it back to the station. I am still on the fence with this and unsure if buying the less expensive model was the right decision.

R699:	First let me say the seller is great. The product was packaged extremely well and arrived very quickly, but that's where the positive comments end. I read TONS of reviews before ordering this and I don't see how everyone is so thrilled with this thing. It has gotten caught (and stops running, flashes red and beeps constantly) EVERY TIME I USE IT. It gets caught on loop pile doorway rugs (very thin rugs), phone chargers, shoes, dog toys, area rugs, etc. Maybe if you have a round room, with NOTHING on the floor you might be able to use the automated/unattended cleaning mode. I would never try it. We run it at home while we are at home and we have to go save it 2-3 times EVERY TIME. I can't imagine waking up at 2AM to the alarm because it got caught on something. The problem with rugs is it that it is very inconsistent in being able to navigate them. These are very thin, extremely low pile rugs that are in the kitchen or at the entrance of a doorway. They loop pile rugs that are thinner than shown in the demo video. Half time time it will run up on the rug no problem, other times it flips the edge of the rug up as if you are rolling up up and then the thing is teetering on the rolled up rug and starts to sound the alarm. We also have two yellow labradors - so we have a few large dog toys. We try to keep the toys put away but heaven forbid they get one out - this thing is going to have a problem. It has also gotten stuck on a phone charger, lamp cord and a pair of shoes. For best results pretend you have company coming (run around and pick up EVERYTHING), turn it on and don't leave it alone. It DOES clean up very well, but that comes at the cost of rescuing it 2-3 times in the hour or so that it cleans the floors. By the third rescue I am so frustrated I just turn it off, empty it - and put it back on the charger.

	PosTag:	[IN, DT, JJ, NN, PRP, VBP, RB, JJ, PRP, RB, VBP, PRP, RP, ,, JJ, PRP, :, CC, VB, PRP, RB, IN, DT, NN, .]

R700:	This is my first self-running vacuum. I use this unit to clean my living room and kitchen floors on the first floor, which needs multiple cleanings a week to battle multiple cats. I find it does a good job cleaning my carpet and kitchen floor. It handles getting around most of my furniture and kitchen table chairs. There are two areas where it gets stuck about half the time, which is under my La-Z-Boy and between my couch and my movie storage tower shelf. The issues I have with it is that it does not map a room. If it does, it's doesn't do it well. If it gets stuck and you rescue it and restart it, it acts like it is cleaning the room for the first time again. So if it gets stuck after cleaning for 45 minutes, it will go back to the spots it has already cleaned. It doesn't appear to avoid walls or furniture. Rather, it just bumps into them and then rotates until it can move forward. You can program it to clean at a certain time of the day, but it cannot be programmed to run only on certain days. So you can turn the timer off for days you don't need it to clean or let it run every single day. I find it takes over an hour to clean the two rooms I allow it access to. So this unit is best used if you don't plan to access those rooms for a while or to run it while you are gone, which for me is a 50/50 risk on it getting stuck. Another issue is where it needs to be stored. The unit needs about three feet of clearance on both sides, which has forced me to place the base in a spot in my living room that is visible to everyone rather than in my kitchen under the table, out of the way. For the money it is a good value, but it lacks features the other units offer. **Update 11-23-2017** After sending a few example videos of issues to Eufy support, they suggested I try the new 11+. They offered to replace my existing one with the 11+ at no extra charge to see if the new one would solve some of the issues. I have tried it for a fews days and the one thing I noticed the 11+ has improved on is its ability to sense walls. It now stops short (most of the time) of running into the walls and will edge around them. It still gets stuck around my La-Z-Boy recliner, so I need to take the time to build blockades around it before using the vacuum. Also, it will still run over things like a pet's raised place-mat where the food bowls sit. So there are improvements, and the unit still does a GREAT job of cleaning the floors and carpet, but there is a ways to go to improve its ability to know it cannot get under certain furniture or to avoid more things sitting on the floor. **Update 12-12-2017** Unfortunately the 11+ busted a wheel trying to get under my recliner. It had pushed the blockade I had setup around it and repeatedly tried to bore into it. When it pushed the recliner back enough to get under it, the weight of the recliner pushed back down on the unit and trapped it. It must have tried to reverse out or something because when I got home it was nearly dead. When I pushed the start button it was flashing to try to get back to its base and I noticed a grinding noise as it limped home. I let it fully charge, cleaned it out, and tried again. It limped out and basically rolled in lazy long circles due to the one wheel not being fully functioning. Eufy support has been excellent at all times. I think they have an excellent way of trying to help customers. Unfortunately this product has issues with any floorspace that has things that need avoiding, even large furniture. Customer service refunded me the money and sent me a shipping label to return the product. This is a great-value product if you can ensure your area is RoboVac-safe. La-Z-Boy Recliners are apparently the worst nemesis for this unit when it comes to furniture.

R708:	I have a labrador retriever at home and purchase this vacuum in the hopes that it would cut down on the daily hair that we have to vacuum up with our upright vacuum. Unfortunately, I found that this only works if you have a.) hard surface floors and b.) if you don't have any mixed floor surfaces. On a hard surface floor such as wood, tile, or concrete, the RoboVac works fine, using its combination of sensors to roam around and find things to vacuum. It has a decent enough (not powerful) vacuum to pick up pet hair, dust, and small crumbs. However, when the RoboVac encounters mixed flooring, such as transitioning from a tile floor to an area rug, it becomes almost worthless, spewing dust and dirt in a trail all over the floor. The problem stems from the fact that the device can't handle being angled in any way. The dust collection bin is located near the rear of the unit and when the device is not totally flat, the dirt and dust simply spills out of the back. The wheel performance is also lacking; twice in the span of 5 minutes the RoboVac got stuck on an area rug about 1/2" thick because it couldn't transition from the rug back to the hard surface. These deficiencies made it painfully obvious that I wouldn't be able to use this because I'd basically come home and need to re-vacuum with my floor with the upright. If you decide to purchase this, hopefully you wont have the same problem I did, but I can say that it will be awhile before I purchase a robotic vacuum. They just aren't ready for primetime yet if you have a floor with a mix of hard surfaces, area rugs, and carpet.

R717:	This is an ok intro to robo vacs, however if I'd paid attention to the return window this would have gone back. It has decent suction, it picks up pet hair and dust from the wood and tile. It's not smart enough to avoid throw rugs and determinedly climbs those suckers and gets stuck. It cries for a few seconds in hopes of getting rescued then shuts down. So when I run it I have to go around and fold all the area rugs in half to prevent the poor thing from being stranded. Its pattern of vacuuming is also bizarre. It just bounces around and frequently cleans the same areas and misses many others. I should have just spent $10 on a dust mop, or $70 more on a roomba. Lesson learned :( Edit 9/8/17 Eufy has been outstanding in their customer service and offering to resolve the problem. If I'd paid attention to the return date, there wouldn't have been an issue, this vacuum just isn't for me. Updating my review from 1 star to 3 stars for great customer service.

R723:	This purchase is my first ever robotic vacuum cleaner. I bought it as part of a Black Friday deal (whopping 52% off) so I thought I would go ahead and give it a shot. The reason for this machine served two purposes: 1. - We have a dog that sheds without ceasing. It’s a daily challenge to try and maintain it. 2. – My daughter will soon be crawling, and we didn’t entertain the idea of her frequent exposure of all the hair on the floor. Setup was rather easy. Open it up and follow the brief instructions. Initial charge time was approx. 4-5 hours. While this little guy can in no way match the power of an upright vacuum cleaner, it did pretty well. When using auto mode it appears that its pathway is completely random. I do not believe that this machine “maps” your home. However, it does seem to get all the spots. It does has some difficulty navigating its way around cords (so much sure you organize or pick them up). With all that said, I like this robotic vacuum. I’ve been quite impressed with the functionality and the amount of dust/debris that it picks up. Every time I run it; it somehow finds more crud to suck up. The dog doesn’t seem to mind it. Excellent purchase if you want to conduct daily maintenance of your floors. I only gave it four stars because it keeps getting stuck in certain areas/scenarios and seems to do better on hardwood vs. carpet. Update: I did want to mention that customer service is very helpful. Several days after posting my review I was contacted by them to help me resolve several issues. I highly recommend this vacuum as they stand behind their product! Update #2: I've lowered this to three stars.After several weeks of ownership, the vacuum roller on the robot keeps getting stuck (it does a 4 beep error code). No matter how often I clean the brush it does this. I continually have to turn it back on. About 10 minutes later it does it again. Same carpet, low ply, no new obstacles. On carpet it appears that this happens when using the "max" mode. Not sure why.

R729:	UPDATE: We loved this thing!! Just moved into our new house and found the box, hooked it up and the maiden voyage filled the dust bin. AFTER A MONTH OR SO, EUFY QUIT GOING HOME. We used the cord to charge and then after another month or so, it just quit. Really disappointed. Granddaughter sprinkled paper confetti stuff to feed it and it caught everything the first week. By the time we started having issues, we were settled into the house, it was just me and husband with fairly clear colors. End update. We've used it so far just downstairs on our tile floor, huge space, and it does travel under couches, under table navigating around chair legs, up onto the area rug, and cleans as you'd hope but may not really expect. My only disappointment is I haven't yet figured out the settings on the remote, but that also could be my granddaughter changing it to goof with me. If I found another great deal and had leftover in my budget, I'd get another to keep one on each floor.

R730:	We bought it seeing the wonderful reviews it has on the site. But seeing it work, there is some practical challenges involved. 1. It does not reach corners or higher areas above the floor..a major disadvantage if you are switching from vacuum cleaners I have not used any other robot vacuum cleaners yet, but I given these practical challenges with these VCs I better move onto more traditional vacuum cleaners

R731:	*** Update*** 1 year of use. When the Eufy is working it's generally great. *When it's working.* In the course of a year I've had to have it replaced 5 times. The process is generally easy and customer service folks for Eufy are helpful. That being said I can't blame this on a "lemon" unit. It's the design and manufacturing of the product that's the problem. Some of the malfunctions were common knowledge to the customer service representatives. I was hoping to get a vacuum that would last me at least a few years for this price. Preferably at least 5. Instead I've passed the year mark of warranty from my original purchase and the company will not replace yet another malfunctioning Eufy. Number 6. I want to like this vacuum but with all the problems, replacements and now still not having a working vacuum it's just not worth the hassle. ***Update*** I've been looking at the iRobot versions for a bit but the price tag was hard to deal with. Eventually found this wonder. Comparing to a few friends that run different models of the iRobot this does just as well at a lot better price point. Would definitely recommend this to anyone and would buy another if it ever breaks. I have wood floors throughout my house with area rugs, two cats and a dog running around. I don't think the floor has ever been so consistently clean. No fur floating around all the time and no litter to walk on with bare feet. The amount I empty out of this thing every day is a bit disturbing but it's great coming home and finding all the rugs and floor clean.

R746:	I purchased this item March 21st. It started giving me issues mid-May, and it continued to do so. The charged base wouldn't charge the unit, and then it started to throw constant codes. It finally came to a point where the unit wouldn't run because it would throw a code. We tried all trouble shooting which we could with the manual at hand. My husband finally contacted Eufy at the beginning of June. Eufy agreed to have us send the defective unit back to them, and they would immediately send us a new one. They sent us a label, and we promptly returned our item. I finally contacted Eufy today (it's June 19th and we sent our item back first week of June) asking the status of our new unit. They had no record of a new one coming our way. Customer service even admitted that if we didn't contact them, they would have not sent us a replacement unit. Then, the agent processes the new unit for us and states it will be 3-5 business days at least. I asked for expedited shipping, and Eufy agreed. I just received tracking, and they shipped it FedEx GROUND! I will not see the new unit until Friday (wrote this review on a Monday). I hate to see how many more weeks it would have taken to receive the new unit if I didn't ask for expedited shipping. I AM NOT PLEASED. I WILL NO LONGER REFER OTHERS TO THIS PRODUCT. In the mean time, since Eufy was taking their merry old time, I bought a Roomba. I'll say the Roomba has better suction, and it does a better job at cleaning too. I can bet Roomba's customer service is MUCH better too. So, all in all, buy an Eufy...but if it fails after less than two months, don't count on their customer service actually following through without you advocating for yourself as a consumer.

R748:	While this ptoduct wasn't adequate for my needs per comments below. The customer service from Eufy was impeccable and i would have no misgivings trying another oc their product offerings. Purchased this a month and a half ago. I've been trying different layouts and blocked it off in certain areas to see if I can get better performance out of it. No luck. Probably going to try to return it if it isn't too late. Good: It is a robot with some suction and brushes. Kind of vacuums. Makes me feel like we are close to the 21st century portrayed in Back to the Future Part II. Bad: Horrible at navigating anything but small rectangular areas. I've got a pretty open dining room kitchen area, it's in the shape of a large L. The Eufy Robovac 11 cleans 80% of it well, 10% of it decent, and consistently misses 10% of the area. The 10% it misses is a 5'x10' foot print close by the home station, not sure if that has anything to do with it and a small space under a table. It really looks like there is NO logic to it's navigation algorithm. It will follow the wall for a minute then decide to shoot across the room, stop at the walk, 45 degree angle, then shoot off in some other random direction. You would think the algorithm would have it maybe navigate the exterior walls to set a boundary, then start 'filling in' the space contained within that boundary. Once it's footprint has passed over every inch without an obstacle it would have successfully robotic-ally vacuumed... I've tried the robovac in other rooms/sizes. It seems to do best in small rectangular areas with no obstacles and light dirt/debris. Any difficulty greater than that and you will start to see gaps in where it vacuumed. It stated it can vacuum on low pile carpeting. I have low pile carpeting in half my house, while it does pull some crud off the carpeting it does not do an adequate job. Still significant amounts of animal hair just laying on top of the surface (see below). While this unit is not rated for animal hair, there were multiple reviews and questions/answers regarding pet hair and the great job this unit does. I'm wondering what actual pets these people have, imaginary maybe? In hind sight I'm guessing these were fake reviews/questions/answers as I have pets and every 10 minutes have to stop the unit because either the brush is full of hair or the robot is clogged between the brush and dust bin. If you have pets and want a robot vacuum do NOT buy this unit. It is not pet compatible. Navigation sensors on board suck. It refuses to go under a bookshelf I have, the lowest shelf is 5-6" off the floor. But if I let it loose in my bedroom it consistently gets stuck under my foot board. I don't understand how it can see the book shelf as a threat/obstacle and yet doesn't see the foot board and when it gets stuck continues to try to drive under it. I bought this with the hopes of getting an adequately vacuumed house (I'm a single male so my standards really aren't that high) with minimal effort. Considering it can't adequately navigate my rooms, the horrible job it does on carpets, and the fact I have to baby it due to pet hair; It completely missed the mark. If you have a simple rectangular area with few obstacles and hard surfaces you should be ok. Any more complexity and you'll be disappointed.

R753:	Updated Review for RoboVac 11s: While the 11S performs well, the replacement unit only lasted 8 months before it just would not turn on anymore. Review for RoboVac 11s: We were given the opportunity to try the RoboVac 11s. The 11s is a much better product. It does not get stuck on our carpets and has many improved features (such as a better brush guard and bigger wheels). The sensors also seem better and it seems to move slower so when it does bump into things it does not do so as hard as the 11. Original Review for RoboVac 11: The RoboVac 11 constantly get's stuck on everything. It will just stop in the middle of a "low-pile" carpet or in-between rooms and beep for a few minutes. Most of the time you can just hit the start button and it will continue to vacuum. That's not helpful when you set the vacuum to run while you're not home. I imagine if you had hard surface floor with zero obstacles the RoboVac would work fine. Additionally, the RoboVac will just bump right into everything. It is supposed to have sensors but instead just runs into chairs, tables, walls, etc. This proves difficult as the RoboVac will push a door open if it is not closed all the way or push things out of the way that you put up to block it in the kitchen so you have to use something heavier than you would expect.

R773:	The vacuum is inexpensive, very quiet, and cleans well where it reaches, including hair from two dogs. We have a relatively house with a very complex floor arrangement (basically an octagon with small additions, rooms arranged in a "U" pattern). We found that we had to block the Eufy in individual rooms or it would only clean part of the house. After discussing this with customer service, which was very responsive, here is the reason. Eufy uses a random "Bounce" method to cover the floor space and has no memory of where it has been. So in our house it bounces around in the first room, may make it to another room or two, but then must go back to the station to recharge. But having no memory it then just starts random bouncing again. On rare occasions it gets caught bouncing back and forth between two objects. If you have a smaller house or apartment with a simple floor arrangement, that would work great. But in our house it seems like carrying it to specific rooms, letting it bounce around, carrying it back to the charger, putting it in a new room after it charges is the only way to get the floors fully clean. But to us that just defeats most of the purpose of using a robot. But if you are willing to do that, or have a small, simpler home then it is a very good, very quiet, inexpensive robot. Fortunately, during the time we have had the Eufy the price of the new Neato Connected dropped $200 so the Eufy almost paid for itself now that we will be replacing it.

R774:	6 month update: Our robovac has become vision challenged. the top might be scratch resistant but the lens in front of it, which covering the infrared sensors has become so scratched that the obstacle avoidance is mostly failing. Poor thing bounces off everything each morning and it's sad to watch. I tried to clean the lens, but it's not working, it's got micro cracks and has started to pull away from the bezel its glued into. My girlfriend and I talked about it last night and we are talking about "putting it down". I looked around online for a replacement lens but came up short. I can recommend a robovac in general but not this model in particular. They need to make the lens scratch resistant as well. After three months... It's been 3 months and we are more than pleased. We bought it as a Prime Day deal, a sort of gift for ourselves in our new house. We have lots of hard floors on one level and while moving it was clear it just will need a lot of sweeping. My gf is more picky about the cleanliness of the house and I could tell I was going to be expected to cater to her expectations of clean and my tolerances wouldn't much matter. So, I saw this as an opportunity to see if the robot was really up to the task. I got it because of the reviews and the price. The competitive brands were pricey. I love features and I'm seduced by anything that is "Alexa Ready", but this time I thought that I'm not really going to need to interface with my vacuum cleaner via Alexa and it wasn't a necessary feature. Most stuff is only 50/50 with the Alexa ecosystem anyway, so one less frustrating device was fine with me. Generally what I'm saying is that this was a cheaper brand and model and it lacked many of the latest bells and whistles of the Roomba's of the world, but I don't know that I need them at this point and we're super happy with the way it carries it out it's basic function/mission: wake up, eat dirt, when you are done, park yourself in your charger. It uses a remote control for basic programming, not a phone/tablet app, which does what you would expect and seems to work fine. If I needed more than simple scheduling and start/stop/steering I would really want an app. In 3 or 4 months, I've used the remote only 3 or 4 times. I scheduled it for early morning cleanings before most of the house wakes. My alarm wakes me before the robot and I hear "her" when she beeps awake at precisely the same time every morning. She has a definite sound, but it's not nearly close to your average push vac. In the quiet of the morning in a house still asleep, she is the prevailing sound. I can't figure out her pattern algorithm, she seemingly has no real plan to cover a room efficiently, she just turns away from obstructions at some angle and keeps going until she senses another barrier and repeats it like a drunk sailor making his way back to the bunks. We have steps and she has never tumbled down over them, even in the dark. We didn't have to put out any sort of electronic fence or strips to keep her contained, but we only use her on one level. Occasionally she manages to move one of the light floor rugs in front of the back door. One morning, early on, I caught her banging into everything like she was blind. Apparently she was. I guess her glasses were dirty. Cleaned the front of her optical sensors and she could see again and went back to her more agile self. Quite frequently, when a baseboard/wall is encountered, she will alternate between "walking" the wall or running a tight line along it and using her extra long "whisking" bristle antenna, cleans right to where the wall and floor meet. I never see a web or a crumb or dust along a baseboard. It's crazy. The biggest plus is that, despite her ADD style of cleaning, she gets the whole living room/kitchen/hallway clean.. every morning. She wakes at 6:15am and by around 8am she decides she is done and thinks about parking. I'm not sure how she decides this, but it's very likely based on time. There is no way she has any sort of indication that she has covered the entire floor, it's too damn random, but efficient or not, most days at 8am, she is parked and the floor is spotless. We've not had to sweep once in three months unless there is some spill that needs to cleaned up now. She can go a week or two before really needing emptied, but I've never waited to be alerted, I just do it as a routine every three or 4 days. She can fit under our couch and our table in the entry way, which would traditionally be an area that would be a dust bunny refuge and only occasionally cleaned. I had to move the couch the other day and had this natural expectation of a dusty horror only to see a mostly spotless floor (some corners were difficult around legs, etc). So far, this thing is awesome. When the machines rise up, we'll be in such denial they will wipe us out in 24 hours. I see me just stepping over the dutiful vacuum early in the AM, and she'll take me out before my first cup of coffee. If only she knew we appreciated her and she was very much a part of the family. #takemefirst

R775:	We bought this for every day cleanup of cat litter, hair, etc. It does the job for the most part! It doesn't have much of a system, just knocks all over the place haphazardly (missing spots occasionally). It does not avoid walls or furniture, just knocks into them (which is fine). It doesn't do a very good job on any type of rug/carpet, just bounces over. Battery life is good for the first 6 months and then it doesn't vacuum for very long. After 13 months of having it.. it stopped running and wouldn't charge. When I spoke to a rep, they're answer was "it's out of warranty, we can give you 15% off your next one." Sooo I wasn't very happy with this answer, as it shows they don't stand behind their product ($180/year for a vacuum?!). After being on hold for a while, a manager came on to tell me it needed a new battery; when it was replaced it's running again just fine... Moral of the story, buy a new battery!

R777:	I loved this vacuum until mine broke. It did a great job cleaning and kept my floor (mix of carpet and tile) much cleaner than when I vacuumed manually. It did a great job of keeping up with a dog who sheds a lot. The dust canister is easy to empty and the filters are easy to clean/replace. Flaw 1: It has a tendency to jam itself under shelves and get stuck. I had to stick shims under the front of two shelving units I had because they were at just the right height for the vacuum to squeeze under them and then get stuck and unable to back itself out. Flaw 2: After 4 months of use one of the side bush motors broke, rendering it unusable. As soon as I turn it on it reports 'Side brush stuck' and no amount of cleaning/removing the brush seems to fix it. In fairness, if my Eufy was still under warranty they would have offered to send a replacement, however I won mine in a contest so it was not covered. However even with the warranty protection I would have hoped that the device would last longer before breaking and/or that it would have better ability to continue working when one part breaks. e.g. I'd be happy to keep using it with only one working side brush, but I don't have that option since it immediately stops and starts beeping every time I try to turn it on.

R779:	The first unit I received kept loosing the side brush and had a loud rattling noise on hard surfaces. Eufy customer service was great to work with and replaced the unit promptly. I've had the second unit now for a little over a month, and it's now making a rattling noise on hard surfaces and also has lost the side brush a few times. I have found that the noise is caused from the main brush wearing and no longer being secure. The way that their brushes are held in needs some work! The plastic wears down and doesn't hold. I have found that a small piece of electrical tape on the socketed end of the brush helps hold in place better. Also, my cat has fine hair and it gets stuck in the brush very easily and is hard to remove. I think Eufy has a great product, but really needs some improvement. I paid only $179. for it here on Amazon. Saw the new price of $269. now, and can tell you it does not warrant that price.

R780:	OK, but didn't replace our daily routine pet vacuuming like we hoped. We have large dog and got Eufy Robovac to help with daily pet hair. Very high quality, well made. Easy to assemble and activate. Seemed reasonable for price compared to Roomba. Simple instructions. Has good suction and strong motor and two sweeping brushes where Roomba has only one. It will handle thick pet hair easily and if you have a very simple house with little furniture and few built-ins and very low 1/4 inch rugs, it is fine. If you have a larger house with complex walls and built-ins and a lot of furniture with thicker carpets 1/2 inch or greater, it struggles a lot and gets stuck every 5 min. The problem is that when it gets stuck on its automatic cycle at 1am, it beeps and beeps for rescue? If it truly gets stuck under something and you don't get it before it stops beeping, it shuts down and won't reply to the remote? Found ours a day later wedged under bedside table after extensive search. So, my opinion is that it's not quite ready for prime time. Honestly the dimensions need to be about 10-20% bigger with larger wheels and ability to handle thicker carpets better.

R782:	On Jan 16, 2019 I purchased a Eufy Model 11C Robotic Vacuum from an Ebay seller. One reason for purchasing this product was it's 12 month warranty. Last week, the machine quit moving on carpet, climbing thresholds, etc. It also quit going around obstacles, instead just bumping them and sitting there. I called Eufy customer service April 8 to request warranty repair for my two month old machine. The CS rep immediately wanted the 'original order number', saying it was the number from when the machine was originally ordered from the factory. I explained where I bought the machine, but was told no number, no repair. The CS rep suggested I contact the seller and see if they had the 'original order number'. He informed me he had won the vacuum and had no idea where it was bought. I wrote customer service yesterday and explained to them what happened. I received an email back with the same story, except Eufy recommended I force either Ebay or the seller to issue a refund! That's right, they actually suggested I try to put my seller and/or Ebay on the spot for Eufy's junk product! I informed Eufy that I had no intention of making someone else pay for their defective product. I urge anyone who is looking at robot vacuums to look right on by the Eufy brand.

R809:	UPDATE I'm so bummed!!! I changed my 5 star to 1 star. We were totally loving our new robovac. And then things changed. We purchased two units to replace a previous Roomba and they initially worked great. However after about five or six weeks the first unit started having problems. About three weeks later our second unit started having the same problems. When the unit bangs into a wall, the sensors will redirect the unit for a new Direction. However, on both of our units, the sensors are getting stuck. And the unit will go in a circle. The only fix we have found is we have to physically knock the sensor unstuck. That typically entails finding wherever the stuck unit is, and very forcefully hitting the front of the unit until the number un sticks. This solution will work for some time, but invariably we will need to reset the unit again some time in the next 5 to 10 minutes. For me, this makes the unit's virtually useless. We bought them to have an unsupervised and automated cleaning of the floors. But when I am forced to find the stuck unit, and physically unstick the sensors every 5 to 10 minutes, it is a complete waste for us. So I guess this just reaffirms the idea between price and value. The Eufy is a great unit when it works and in my opinion preferable to the Roomba. But the quality is not there and it does not last. If this only happened to one of our units I would chalk it up to bad luck. But since both units are experiencing the exact same problem within a period of three weeks apart, it seems clear it's a quality issue. ORIGINAL POST AND REVIEW Wow! Totally love it! We had been loyal iRobot/Roomba users for years. Our Roomba did a pretty decent job for the 3 years we had it and thought things were pretty good. When our last Roomba (360) finally died, we decided to try something new and bought 2 of these. We have hard wood and ceramic tile floors. We also have three BIG dogs that have a dog door that they are in and out of all day and drag in tons of dirt. Our floors are a full time job to keep clean! We placed one upstairs and one on our main floor and programmed them to run once/day. The results have been awesome! Our floors have truly never been cleaner. We've only had them for about a week, so I can't report on the long term durability of the Eufy's, but will update my posting as we learn more. I listed several key characteristics that I thought would be helpful in making a decision. Overall Satisfaction Eufy ~ 5 Roomba ~ 3.5 Running Time Eufy ~ 5 Roomba ~ 5 Noise Level Eufy ~ 5 (super quiet!) Roomba ~ 2 (can't talk on phone it's so loud) Roomba seemed to bang into things ALOT and just didn't seem to cover the floors very well. The Eufy seems to have a much better sensor system and doesn't bang into things nearly as much, but also seems to have a better algorithm to cover the floors better. Efficiency Eufy ~ 5 Roomba ~ 3.5 Features Eufy ~ 5 Roomba ~ 3.5 Eufy comes with a remote control that makes it super easy to program, and also gives the ability to remotely start it, re-direct it to dirty spots, set "Max" cleaning, and more.
